# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: transmission-distribution
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] A **distribution transformer** or **service** **transformer** is a transformer that provides a final voltage reduction in the electric power distribution system, stepping down the voltage used in the distribution lines to the level used by the customer.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] The invention of a practical, efficient transformer made AC power distribution feasible; a system using distribution transformers was demonstrated as early as 1882.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] If mounted on a utility pole, they are called pole-mount transformers.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] When placed either at ground level or underground, distribution transformers are mounted on concrete pads and locked in steel cases, thus known as distribution tap pad-mounted transformers.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] Distribution transformers typically have ratings less than 200 kVA, although some national standards allow units up to 5000 kVA to be described as distribution transformers.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] Since distribution transformers are energized 24 hours a day (even when they don't carry any load), reducing iron losses is vital in their design.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] They usually don't operate at full load, so they are designed to have maximum efficiency at lower loads.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] To have better efficiency, voltage regulation in these transformers is kept to a minimum.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] Hence, they are designed to have small leakage reactance.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] Distribution transformers are normally located at a service drop, where wires run from a utility pole or underground power lines to a customer's premises.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] They are often used for the power supply of facilities outside settlements, such as isolated houses, farmyards, or pumping stations at voltages below 30 kV.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] Another application is the power supply of the overhead wire of railways electrified with AC.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] In this case, single-phase distribution transformers are used.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] The number of customers fed by a single distribution transformer varies depending on the number of customers in an area.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] Several homes may be fed from a single transformer in urban areas; depending on the mains voltage, rural distribution may require one transformer per customer.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] A large commercial or industrial complex will have multiple distribution transformers.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] In urban areas and neighborhoods where primary distribution lines run underground, padmount transformers, and locked metal enclosures are mounted on a concrete pad.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] Many large buildings have electric service provided at primary distribution voltage.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] These buildings have customer-owned transformers in the basement for step-down purposes.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] Distribution transformers are also found in wind farm power collection networks, where they step up power from each wind turbine to connect to a substation that may be several miles (kilometers) distant.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] Both pole-mounted and pad-mounted transformers convert the overhead or underground distribution lines' high *primary* voltage to the lower *secondary* or utilization voltage inside the building.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] The primary distribution wires use the three-phase system.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] Main distribution lines always have three "hot" wires plus an optional neutral.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] In the North American system, where single-phase transformers connect to only one phase wire, smaller lateral lines branching off on side roads may include only one or two hot phase wires.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] When only one phase wire exists, a neutral will always be provided as a return path.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] Primaries provide power at the standard distribution voltages used in the area; these range from as low as 2.3 kV to about 35 kV depending on local distribution practice and standards, often 11 kV (50 Hz systems) and 13.8 kV (60 Hz systems) are used, but many other voltages are standard.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] For example, in the United States, the most common voltage is 12.47 kV, with a line-to-ground voltage of 7.2 kV.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] It has a 7.2 kV phase-to-neutral voltage, exactly 30 times the 240 V on the split-phase secondary side.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] The high-voltage primary windings are brought out to bushings on the top of the case.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] The transformer is always connected to the primary distribution lines through protective fuses and disconnect switches.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] For pole-mounted transformers, this is usually a fused cutout.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] An electrical fault melts the fuse, and the device drops open to give a visual indication of trouble.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] Lineworkers can also manually open it while the line is energized using insulated hot sticks.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] In some cases, completely self-protected transformers are used, which have a circuit breaker built in, so a fused cutout isn't needed.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] The low-voltage secondary windings are attached to three or four terminals on the transformer's side.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] Distribution transformers consist of a magnetic core made from laminations of sheet silicon steel (transformer steel) stacked and either glued together with resin or banded together with steel straps, with the primary and secondary wire windings wrapped around them.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] This core construction is designed to reduce core losses and dissipation of magnetic energy as heat in the core, an economically important cause of power loss in utility grids.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] Two effects cause core losses: hysteresis loss in the steel and eddy currents.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] Silicon steel has low hysteresis loss, and the laminated construction prevents eddy currents from flowing in the core, which dissipates power in the resistance of the steel.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] The efficiency of typical distribution transformers is between about 98 and 99 percent.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] Where large numbers of transformers are made to standard designs, a wound C-shaped core is economical to manufacture.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] A steel strip is wrapped around a former, pressed into shape, and then cut into two C-shaped halves re-assembled on the copper windings.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] The primary coils are wound from enamel-coated copper or aluminum wire, and the high-current, low-voltage secondaries are wound using a thick ribbon of aluminum or copper.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] The windings are insulated with resin-impregnated paper.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] The entire assembly is baked to cure the resin and then submerged in a powder-coated steel tank, which is then filled with transformer oil (or other insulating liquid), which is inert and non-conductive.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] The transformer oil cools and insulates the windings and protects them from moisture.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] The tank is temporarily evacuated during manufacture to remove any remaining moisture that would cause arcing and is sealed against the weather with a gasket at the top.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] Formerly, distribution transformers for indoor use would be filled with a polychlorinated biphenyl (PCB) liquid.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] Because these chemicals persist in the environment and adversely affect on animals, they have been banned.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] Other fire-resistant liquids such as silicones are used where a liquid-filled transformer must be used indoors.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] Certain vegetable oils have been applied as transformer oil; these have the advantage of a high fire point and are completely biodegradable in the environment.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] Pole-mounted transformers often include accessories such as surge arresters or protective fuse links.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] A self-protected transformer consists of an internal fuse and surge arrester; other transformers have these components mounted separately outside the tank.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] Pole-mounted transformers may have lugs allowing direct mounting to a pole or may be mounted on cross-arms bolted to the pole.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] Aerial transformers, larger than around 75 kVA, may be mounted on a platform supported by one or more poles.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] A three-phase service may use three identical transformers, one per phase.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] Transformers engineered for below-grade applications may be designed for periodic submersion, particularly in areas with high water tables or flood risks.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] Distribution transformers may include an off-load tap changer, which slightly adjusts the ratio between primary and secondary voltage to bring the customer's voltage within the desired range on long or heavily loaded lines.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] Pad-mounted transformers have secure locked, bolted, and grounded metal enclosures to discourage unauthorized access to live internal parts.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] The enclosure may also include fuses, isolating switches, load-break bushings, and other accessories as described in technical standards.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] Pad-mounted transformers for distribution systems typically range from around 100 to 2000 kVA, although some larger units are also used.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] In the United States, distribution transformers are often installed outdoors on wooden poles.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] In Europe, it is most common to place them in buildings.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] If the feeding lines are overhead, these look like towers.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] If all lines running to the transformer are underground, small buildings are used.
[src:transmission-distribution/distribution-transformer] In rural areas, sometimes distribution transformers are mounted on poles, and the pole is usually made of concrete or iron due to the weight of the transformer.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Transmission lines transmit either alternating current (AC) or direct current (DC).
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] To increase the efficiency of long-distance electric power transmission, the voltage is often increased for transmission, then reduced for local distribution.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] This is because higher voltages corresponds to lower currents and lower losses caused by such currents.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The AC voltage level is often changed with transformers.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] A wide area synchronous grid, known as an *interconnection* in North America, directly connects generators delivering AC power with the same relative *frequency* to many consumers.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] North America has four major interconnections: Western, Eastern, Quebec and Texas.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] One grid connects most of continental Europe.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Historically, transmission and distribution lines were often owned by the same company, but starting in the 1990s, many countries liberalized the regulation of the electricity market in ways that led to separate companies handling transmission and distribution.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Most North American transmission lines are high-voltage three-phase AC, although single phase AC is sometimes used in railway electrification systems.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] DC technology is used for greater efficiency over longer distances, typically hundreds of miles.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] High-voltage direct current (HVDC) technology is also used in submarine power cables (typically longer than 30 miles (50 km)), and in the interchange of power between grids that are not mutually synchronized.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] HVDC links stabilize power distribution networks where sudden new loads, or blackouts, in one part of a network might otherwise result in synchronization problems and cascading failures.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Electricity is transmitted at high voltages to reduce the energy loss due to resistance that occurs over long distances.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Power is usually transmitted through overhead power lines.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Underground power transmission has a significantly higher installation cost and greater operational limitations, but lowers maintenance costs.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Underground transmission is more common in urban areas or visually sensitive locations.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Electrical energy must typically be generated at the same rate at which it is consumed.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] A sophisticated control system is required to ensure that power generation closely matches demand.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] If demand exceeds supply, the imbalance can cause generation plant(s) and transmission equipment to automatically disconnect or shut down to prevent damage.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] In the worst case, this may lead to a cascading series of shutdowns and a major regional blackout.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The US Northeast faced blackouts in 1965, 1977, 2003, and major blackouts in other US regions in 1996 and 2011.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Electric transmission networks are interconnected into regional, national, and even continent-wide networks to reduce the risk of such a failure by providing multiple redundant, alternative routes for power to flow should such shutdowns occur.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Transmission companies determine the maximum reliable capacity of each line (ordinarily less than its physical or thermal limit) to ensure that spare capacity is available in the event of a failure in another part of the network.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The conductor consists of seven strands of steel surrounded by four layers of aluminium.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] High-voltage overhead conductors are not covered by insulation.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The conductor material is usually an aluminium alloy, formed of several strands and possibly reinforced with steel strands.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Copper was sometimes used for overhead transmission, but aluminum is lighter, reduces yields only marginally and costs much less.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Overhead conductors are supplied by several companies.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Conductor material and shapes are regularly improved to increase capacity.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Conductor sizes range from 12 mm2 (#6 American wire gauge) to 1,092 mm2 (2,156,000 circular mils area), with varying resistance and current-carrying capacity.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] For large conductors (more than a few centimetres in diameter), much of the current flow is concentrated near the surface due to the skin effect.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The center of the conductor carries little current but contributes weight and cost.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Thus, multiple parallel cables (called bundle conductors) are used for higher capacity.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Bundle conductors are used at high voltages to reduce energy loss caused by corona discharge.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Today, transmission-level voltages are usually considered to be 110 kV and above.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Lower voltages, such as 66 kV and 33 kV, are usually considered subtransmission voltages, but are occasionally used on long lines with light loads.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Voltages less than 33 kV are usually used for distribution.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Voltages above 765 kV are considered extra high voltage and require different designs.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Increased ambient temperatures during extreme heat events can reduce the efficiency of electrical transmission and distribution, especially in overhead systems.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Thermal expansion causes overhead lines to sag, reducing current flow and increasing the risk of unintended arc discharge if there is vegetation nearby.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Overhead transmission wires depend on air for insulation, requiring that lines maintain minimum clearances.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Adverse weather conditions, such as high winds and low temperatures, interrupt transmission.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Wind speeds as low as 23 knots (43 km/h) can permit conductors to encroach operating clearances, resulting in a flashover and loss of supply.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Oscillatory motion of the physical line is termed conductor gallop or flutter depending on the frequency and amplitude of oscillation.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Electric power can be transmitted by underground power cables.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Underground cables take up no right-of-way, have lower visibility, and are less affected by weather.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Cable and excavation costs are much higher than overhead construction.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Faults in buried transmission lines take longer to locate and repair.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] In some metropolitan areas, cables are enclosed by metal pipe and insulated with dielectric fluid (usually an oil) that is either static or circulated via pumps.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] If an electric fault damages the pipe and leaks dielectric, liquid nitrogen is used to freeze portions of the pipe to enable draining and repair.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] This extends the repair period and increases costs.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The temperature of the pipe and surroundings are monitored throughout the repair period.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Underground lines are limited by their thermal capacity, which permits less overload or re-rating lines.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Long underground AC cables have significant capacitance, which reduces their ability to provide useful power beyond 50 miles (80 kilometres).
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] DC cables are not limited in length by their capacitance.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Commercial electric power was initially transmitted at the same voltage used by lighting and mechanical loads.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] This restricted the distance between generating plant and loads.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] In 1882, DC voltage could not easily be increased for long-distance transmission.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Different classes of loads (for example, lighting, fixed motors, and traction/railway systems) required different voltages, and so used different generators and circuits.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Thus, generators were sited near their loads, a practice that later became known as distributed generation using large numbers of small generators.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Transmission of alternating current (AC) became possible after Lucien Gaulard and John Dixon Gibbs built what they called the secondary generator, an early transformer provided with 1:1 turn ratio and open magnetic circuit, in 1881.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The first long distance AC line was 34 kilometres (21 miles) long, built for the 1884 International Exhibition of Electricity in Turin, Italy.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] It was powered by a 2 kV, 130 Hz Siemens & Halske alternator and featured several Gaulard transformers with primary windings connected in series, which fed incandescent lamps.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The system proved the feasibility of AC electric power transmission over long distances.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The first commercial AC distribution system entered service in 1885 in via dei Cerchi, Rome, Italy, for public lighting.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] It was powered by two Siemens & Halske alternators rated 30 hp (22 kW), 2 kV at 120 Hz and used 19 km of cables and 200 parallel-connected 2 kV to 20 V step-down transformers provided with a closed magnetic circuit, one for each lamp.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] A few months later it was followed by the first British AC system, serving Grosvenor Gallery.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] It also featured Siemens alternators and 2.4 kV to 100 V step-down transformers – one per user – with shunt-connected primaries.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Working to improve what he considered an impractical Gaulard-Gibbs design, electrical engineer William Stanley, Jr. developed the first practical series AC transformer in 1885.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Working with the support of George Westinghouse, in 1886 he demonstrated a transformer-based AC lighting system in Great Barrington, Massachusetts.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] It was powered by a steam engine-driven 500 V Siemens generator.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Voltage was stepped down to 100 volts using the Stanley transformer to power incandescent lamps at 23 businesses over 4,000 feet (1,200 m).
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] This practical demonstration of a transformer and alternating current lighting system led Westinghouse to begin installing AC systems later that year.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] In 1888 the first designs for an AC motor appeared.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] These were induction motors running on polyphase current, independently invented by Galileo Ferraris and Nikola Tesla.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Practical three-phase motors were designed by Mikhail Dolivo-Dobrovolsky and Charles Eugene Lancelot Brown.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Widespread use of such motors were delayed many years by development problems and the scarcity of polyphase power systems needed to power them.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] In the late 1880s and early 1890s smaller electric companies merged into larger corporations such as Ganz and AEG in Europe and General Electric and Westinghouse Electric in the US.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] These companies developed AC systems, but the technical difference between direct and alternating current systems required a much longer technical merger.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Alternating current's economies of scale with large generating plants and long-distance transmission slowly added the ability to link all the loads.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] These included single phase AC systems, poly-phase AC systems, low voltage incandescent lighting, high-voltage arc lighting, and existing DC motors in factories and street cars.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] In what became a universal system, these technological differences were temporarily bridged via the rotary converters and motor-generators that allowed the legacy systems to connect to the AC grid.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] These stopgaps were slowly replaced as older systems were retired or upgraded.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The first transmission of single-phase alternating current using high voltage came in Oregon in 1890 when power was delivered from a hydroelectric plant at Willamette Falls to the city of Portland 14 miles (23 km) down river.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The first three-phase alternating current using high voltage took place in 1891 during the international electricity exhibition in Frankfurt.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] A 15 kV transmission line, approximately 175 km long, connected Lauffen on the Neckar and Frankfurt.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Transmission voltages increased throughout the 20th century.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] By 1914, fifty-five transmission systems operating at more than 70 kV were in service.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The highest voltage then used was 150 kV.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Interconnecting multiple generating plants over a wide area reduced costs.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The most efficient plants could be used to supply varying loads during the day.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Reliability was improved and capital costs were reduced, because stand-by generating capacity could be shared over many more customers and a wider area.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Remote and low-cost sources of energy, such as hydroelectric power or mine-mouth coal, could be exploited to further lower costs.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The 20th century's rapid industrialization made electrical transmission lines and grids critical infrastructure.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Interconnection of local generation plants and small distribution networks was spurred by World War I, when large electrical generating plants were built by governments to power munitions factories.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] These networks use components such as power lines, cables, circuit breakers, switches and transformers.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The transmission network is usually administered on a regional basis by an entity such as a regional transmission organization or transmission system operator.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Transmission efficiency is improved at higher voltage and lower current.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The reduced current reduces heating losses.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Joule's first law states that energy losses are proportional to the square of the current.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Thus, reducing the current by a factor of two lowers the energy lost to conductor resistance by a factor of four for any given size of conductor.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The optimum size of a conductor for a given voltage and current can be estimated by Kelvin's law for conductor size, which states that size is optimal when the annual cost of energy wasted in resistance is equal to the annual capital charges of providing the conductor.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] At times of lower interest rates and low commodity costs, Kelvin's law indicates that thicker wires are optimal.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Otherwise, thinner conductors are indicated.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Since power lines are designed for long-term use, Kelvin's law is used in conjunction with long-term estimates of the price of copper and aluminum as well as interest rates.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Higher voltage is achieved in AC circuits by using a *step-up transformer*.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] High-voltage direct current (HVDC) systems require relatively costly conversion equipment that may be economically justified for particular projects such as submarine cables and longer distance high capacity point-to-point transmission.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] HVDC is necessary for sending energy between unsynchronized grids.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] A transmission grid is a network of power stations, transmission lines, and substations.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Energy is usually transmitted within a grid with three-phase AC.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Single-phase AC is used only for distribution to end users since it is not usable for large polyphase induction motors.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] In the 19th century, two-phase transmission was used but required either four wires or three wires with unequal currents.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Higher order phase systems require more than three wires, but deliver little or no benefit.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] While the price of generating capacity is high, energy demand is variable, making it often cheaper to import needed power than to generate it locally.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Because loads often rise and fall together across large areas, power often comes from distant sources.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Because of the economic benefits of load sharing, wide area transmission grids may span countries and even continents.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Interconnections between producers and consumers enables power to flow even if some links are inoperative.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The slowly varying portion of demand is known as the *base load* and is generally served by large facilities with constant operating costs, termed firm power.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Such facilities are nuclear, coal or hydroelectric, while other energy sources such as concentrated solar thermal and geothermal power have the potential to provide firm power.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Renewable energy sources, such as solar photovoltaics, wind, wave, and tidal, are, due to their intermittency, not considered to be firm.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The remaining or *peak* power demand, is supplied by peaking power plants, which are typically smaller, faster-responding, and higher cost sources, such as combined cycle or combustion turbine plants typically fueled by natural gas.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] New York often buys over 1000 MW of low-cost hydropower from Canada.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Local sources (even if more expensive and infrequently used) can protect the power supply from weather and other disasters that can disconnect distant suppliers.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Hydro and wind sources cannot be moved closer to big cities, and solar costs are lowest in remote areas where local power needs are nominal.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Connection costs can determine whether any particular renewable alternative is economically realistic.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Costs can be prohibitive for transmission lines, but high capacity, long distance super grid transmission network costs could be recovered with modest usage fees.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] At power stations, power is produced at a relatively low voltage between about 480 V and 22 kV, depending on the size of the unit.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The voltage is then stepped up by the power station transformer to a higher voltage (100 kV to 1,000 kV AC) for transmission.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] In the United States, power transmission is, variously, 230 kV to 500 kV, with less than 230 kV or more than 500 kV as exceptions.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The Western Interconnection has two primary interchange voltages: 500 kV AC at 60 Hz, and ±500 kV (1,000 kV net) DC from North to South (Columbia River to Southern California) and Northeast to Southwest (Utah to Southern California).
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The 287.5 kV (Hoover Dam to Los Angeles line, via Victorville) and 345 kV (Arizona Public Service (APS) line) are local standards, both of which were implemented before 500 kV became practical.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Transmitting electricity at high voltage reduces the fraction of energy lost to Joule heating, which varies by conductor type, the current, and the transmission distance.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] For example, a 100 miles (160 km) span at 765 kV carrying 1000 MW of power can have losses of 0.5% to 1.1%.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] A 345 kV line carrying the same load across the same distance has losses of 4.2%.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] For a given amount of power, a higher voltage reduces the current and thus the resistive losses.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] For example, raising the voltage by a factor of 10 reduces the current by a corresponding factor of 10 and therefore the $I^{2}R$ losses by a factor of 100, provided the same sized conductors are used in both cases.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Even if the conductor size (cross-sectional area) is decreased ten-fold to match the lower current, the $I^{2}R$ losses are still reduced ten-fold using the higher voltage.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] While power loss can also be reduced by increasing the wire's conductance (by increasing its cross-sectional area), larger conductors are heavier and more expensive.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] And since conductance is proportional to cross-sectional area, resistive power loss is only reduced proportionally with increasing cross-sectional area, providing a much smaller benefit than the squared reduction provided by multiplying the voltage.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Long-distance transmission is typically done with overhead lines at voltages of 115 to 1,200 kV.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] At higher voltages, where more than 2,000 kV exists between conductor and ground, corona discharge losses are so large that they can offset the lower resistive losses in the line conductors.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Measures to reduce corona losses include larger conductor diameter, hollow cores or conductor bundles.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Factors that affect resistance and thus loss include temperature, spiraling, and the skin effect.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Spiraling, which refers to the way stranded conductors spiral about the center, also contributes to increases in conductor resistance.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The skin effect causes the effective resistance to increase at higher AC frequencies.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Corona and resistive losses can be estimated using a mathematical model.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] US transmission and distribution losses were estimated at 6.6% in 1997, 6.5% in 2007 and 5% from 2013 to 2019.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] In general, losses are estimated from the discrepancy between power produced (as reported by power plants) and power sold; the difference constitutes transmission and distribution losses, assuming no utility theft occurs.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] As of 1980, the longest cost-effective distance for DC transmission was 7,000 kilometres (4,300 miles).
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] For AC it was 4,000 kilometres (2,500 miles), though US transmission lines are substantially shorter.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] In any AC line, conductor inductance and capacitance can be significant.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Currents that flow solely in reaction to these properties, (which together with the resistance define the impedance) constitute reactive power flow, which transmits no power to the load.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] These reactive currents, however, cause extra heating losses.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The ratio of real power transmitted to the load to apparent power (the product of a circuit's voltage and current, without reference to phase angle) is the power factor.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] As reactive current increases, reactive power increases and power factor decreases.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] For transmission systems with low power factor, losses are higher than for systems with high power factor.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Utilities add capacitor banks, reactors and other components (such as phase-shifters; static VAR compensators; and flexible AC transmission systems, FACTS) throughout the system help to compensate for the reactive power flow, reduce the losses in power transmission and stabilize system voltages.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] These measures are collectively called 'reactive support'.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Current flowing through transmission lines induces a magnetic field that surrounds the lines of each phase and affects the inductance of the surrounding conductors of other phases.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The conductors' mutual inductance is partially dependent on the physical orientation of the lines with respect to each other.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Three-phase lines are conventionally strung with phases separated vertically.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The mutual inductance seen by a conductor of the phase in the middle of the other two phases is different from the inductance seen on the top/bottom.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Unbalanced inductance among the three conductors is problematic because it may force the middle line to carry a disproportionate amount of the total power transmitted.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Similarly, an unbalanced load may occur if one line is consistently closest to the ground and operates at a lower impedance.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Because of this phenomenon, conductors must be periodically transposed along the line so that each phase sees equal time in each relative position to balance out the mutual inductance seen by all three phases.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] To accomplish this, line position is swapped at specially designed transposition towers at regular intervals along the line using various transposition schemes.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Subtransmission runs at relatively lower voltages.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] It is uneconomical to connect all distribution substations to the high main transmission voltage, because that equipment is larger and more expensive.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Typically, only larger substations connect with this high voltage.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Voltage is stepped down before the current is sent to smaller substations.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Subtransmission circuits are usually arranged in loops so that a single line failure does not stop service to many customers for more than a short time.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Loops can be *normally closed*, where loss of one circuit should result in no interruption, or *normally open* where substations can switch to a backup supply.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] While subtransmission circuits are usually carried on overhead lines, in urban areas buried cable may be used.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The lower-voltage subtransmission lines use less right-of-way and simpler structures; undergrounding is less difficult.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] No fixed cutoff separates subtransmission and transmission, or subtransmission and distribution.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Voltages of 69 kV, 115 kV, and 138 kV are often used for subtransmission in North America.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] As power systems evolved, voltages formerly used for transmission were used for subtransmission, and subtransmission voltages became distribution voltages.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Like transmission, subtransmission moves relatively large amounts of power, and like distribution, subtransmission covers an area instead of just point-to-point.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Substation transformers reduce the voltage to a lower level for distribution to customers.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] This distribution is accomplished with a combination of sub-transmission (33 to 138 kV) and distribution (3.3 to 25 kV).
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Finally, at the point of use, the energy is transformed to end-user voltage (100 to 4160 volts).
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] High-voltage power transmission allows for lesser resistive losses over long distances.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] This efficiency delivers a larger proportion of the generated power to the loads.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] In a simplified model, the grid delivers electricity from an ideal voltage source with voltage V , delivering a power $P_{V}$ ) to a single point of consumption, modelled by a resistance R , when the wires are long enough to have a significant resistance $R_{C}$ .
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] If the resistances are in series with no intervening transformer, the circuit acts as a voltage divider, because the same current $I={\frac {V}{R+R_{C}}}$ runs through the wire resistance and the powered device.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] For $a>1$ (i.e. conversion of high voltage to low voltage near the consumption point), a larger fraction of the generator's power is transmitted to the consumption point and a lesser fraction is lost to Joule heating.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The terminal characteristics of the transmission line are the voltage and current at the sending (S) and receiving (R) ends.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The line is assumed to be a reciprocal, symmetrical network, meaning that the receiving and sending labels can be switched with no consequence.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The parameters *A*, *B*, *C*, and *D* differ depending on how the desired model handles the line's resistance (*R*), inductance (*L*), capacitance (*C*), and shunt (parallel, leak) conductance *G*.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The four main models are the short line approximation, the medium line approximation, the long line approximation (with distributed parameters), and the lossless line.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] In such models, a capital letter such as *R* refers to the total quantity summed over the line and a lowercase letter such as *c* refers to the per-unit-length quantity.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The lossless line approximation is the least accurate; it is typically used on short lines where the inductance is much greater than the resistance.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] For this approximation, the voltage and current are identical at the sending and receiving ends.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The characteristic impedance is pure real, which means resistive for that impedance, and it is often called surge impedance.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] When a lossless line is terminated by surge impedance, the voltage does not drop.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Though the phase angles of voltage and current are rotated, the magnitudes of voltage and current remain constant along the line.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] For load > SIL, the voltage drops from sending end and the line *consumes* VARs.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] For load < SIL, the voltage increases from the sending end, and the line *generates* VARs.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The short line approximation is normally used for lines shorter than 80 km (50 mi).
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] There, only a series impedance *Z* is considered, while *C* and *G* are ignored.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The final result is that A = D = 1 per unit, B = Z Ohms, and C = 0.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The medium line approximation is used for lines running between 80 and 250 km (50 and 155 mi).
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The series impedance and the shunt (current leak) conductance are considered, placing half of the shunt conductance at each end of the line.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] This circuit is often referred to as a *nominal *π* (pi)* circuit because of the shape (*π*) that is taken on when leak conductance is placed on both sides of the circuit diagram.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The long line model is used when a higher degree of accuracy is needed or when the line under consideration is more than 250 km (160 mi) long.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Series resistance and shunt conductance are considered to be distributed parameters, such that each differential length of the line has a corresponding differential series impedance and shunt admittance.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The following result can be applied at any point along the transmission line, where $\gamma$ is the propagation constant.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] To find the voltage and current at the end of the long line, x should be replaced with l (the line length) in all parameters of the transmission matrix.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] This model applies the Telegrapher's equations.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] High-voltage direct current (HVDC) is used to transmit large amounts of power over long distances or for interconnections between asynchronous grids.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] When electrical energy is transmitted over very long distances, the power lost in AC transmission becomes appreciable and it is less expensive to use direct current instead.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] For a long transmission line, these lower losses (and reduced construction cost of a DC line) can offset the cost of the required converter stations at each end.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] HVDC is used for long submarine cables where AC cannot be used because of cable capacitance.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] In these cases special high-voltage cables are used.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Submarine connections up to 600 kilometres (370 mi) in length have been deployed.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] HVDC links can be used to control grid problems.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The power transmitted by an AC line increases as the phase angle between source end voltage and destination ends increases, but too large a phase angle allows the systems at either end to fall out of step.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Since the power flow in a DC link is controlled independently of the phases of the AC networks that it connects, this phase angle limit does not exist, and a DC link is always able to transfer its full rated power.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] A DC link therefore stabilizes the AC grid at either end, since power flow and phase angle can then be controlled independently.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] As an example, to adjust the flow of AC power on a hypothetical line between Seattle and Boston would require adjustment of the relative phase of the two regional electrical grids.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] This is an everyday occurrence in AC systems, but one that can become disrupted when AC system components fail and place unexpected loads on the grid.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] (and possibly in other cooperating cities along the transmission route).
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Such a system could be less prone to failure if parts of it were suddenly shut down.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] One example of a long DC transmission line is the Pacific DC Intertie located in the Western United States.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The amount of power that can be sent over a transmission line varies with the length of the line.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The heating of short line conductors due to line losses sets a thermal limit.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] If too much current is drawn, conductors may sag too close to the ground, or conductors and equipment may overheat.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] For intermediate-length lines on the order of 100 kilometres (62 miles), the limit is set by the voltage drop in the line.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] For longer AC lines, system stability becomes the limiting factor.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Approximately, the power flowing over an AC line is proportional to the cosine of the phase angle of the voltage and current at the ends.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] This angle varies depending on system loading.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] It is undesirable for the angle to approach 90 degrees, as the power flowing decreases while resistive losses remain.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The product of line length and maximum load is approximately proportional to the square of the system voltage.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Series capacitors or phase-shifting transformers are used on long lines to improve stability.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] HVDC lines are restricted only by thermal and voltage drop limits, since the phase angle is not material.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Understanding the temperature distribution along the cable route became possible with the introduction of distributed temperature sensing (DTS) systems that measure temperatures all along the cable.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Without them maximum current was typically set as a compromise between understanding of operation conditions and risk minimization.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] This monitoring solution uses passive optical fibers as temperature sensors, either inside a high-voltage cable or externally mounted on the cable insulation.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] For overhead cables the fiber is integrated into the core of a phase wire.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The integrated Dynamic Cable Rating (DCR)/Real Time Thermal Rating (RTTR) solution makes it possible to run the network to its maximum.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] It allows the operator to predict the behavior of the transmission system to reflect major changes to its initial operating conditions.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Some utilities have embraced reconductoring to handle the increase in electricity production.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Reconductoring is the replacement-in-place of existing transmission lines with higher-capacity lines.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Adding transmission lines is difficult due to cost, permit intervals, and local opposition.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Reconductoring has the potential to double the amount of electricity that can travel across a transmission line.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] A 2024 report found the United States behind countries like Belgium and the Netherlands in adoption of this technique to accommodate electrification and renewable energy.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] In April 2022, the Biden Administration streamlined environmental reviews for such projects, and in May 2022 announced competitive grants for them funded by the 2021 Bipartisan Infrastructure Law and 2022 Inflation Reduction Act.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The rate of transmission expansion needs to double to support ongoing electrification and reach emission reduction targets.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] As of 2022, more than 10,000 power plant and energy storage projects were awaiting permission to connect to the US grid — 95% were zero-carbon resources.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] New power lines can take 10 years to plan, permit, and build.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Traditional power lines use a steel core surrounded by aluminum strands (Aluminium-conductor steel-reinforced cable).
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Replacing the steel with a lighter, stronger composite material such as carbon fiber (ACCC conductor) allows lines to operate at higher temperatures, with less sag, and doubled transmission capacity.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Lowering line sag at high temperatures can prevent wildfires from starting when power lines touch dry vegetation.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Although advanced lines can cost 2-4x more than steel, total reconductoring costs are less than half of a new line, given savings in time, land acquisition, permitting, and construction.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] A reconductoring project in southeastern Texas upgraded 240 miles of transmission lines at a cost of $900,000 per mile, versus a 3,600-mile greenfield project that averaged $1.9 million per mile.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] To ensure safe and predictable operation, system components are controlled with generators, switches, circuit breakers and loads.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The voltage, power, frequency, load factor, and reliability capabilities of the transmission system are designed to provide cost effective performance.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The transmission system provides for base load and peak load capability, with margins for safety and fault tolerance.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Peak load times vary by region largely due to the industry mix.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] In hot and cold climates home air conditioning and heating loads affect the overall load.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] They are typically highest in the late afternoon in the hottest part of the year and in mid-mornings and mid-evenings in the coldest part of the year.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Power requirements vary by season and time of day.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Distribution system designs always take the base load and the peak load into consideration.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The transmission system usually does not have a large buffering capability to match loads with generation.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Thus generation has to be kept matched to the load, to prevent overloading generation equipment.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Multiple sources and loads can be connected to the transmission system and they must be controlled to provide orderly transfer of power.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] In centralized power generation, only local control of generation is necessary.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] This involves synchronization of the generation units.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] In distributed power generation the generators are geographically distributed and the process to bring them online and offline must be carefully controlled.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The load control signals can either be sent on separate lines or on the power lines themselves.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Voltage and frequency can be used as signaling mechanisms to balance the loads.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] In voltage signaling, voltage is varied to increase generation.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The power added by any system increases as the line voltage decreases.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] This arrangement is stable in principle.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Voltage-based regulation is complex to use in mesh networks, since the individual components and setpoints would need to be reconfigured every time a new generator is added to the mesh.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] In frequency signaling, the generating units match the frequency of the power transmission system.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] In droop speed control, if the frequency decreases, the power is increased.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Wind turbines, vehicle-to-grid, virtual power plants, and other locally distributed storage and generation systems can interact with the grid to improve system operation.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Internationally, a slow move from a centralized to decentralized power systems have taken place.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The main draw of locally distributed generation systems is that they reduce transmission losses by leading to consumption of electricity closer to where it was produced.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Under excess load conditions, the system can be designed to fail incrementally rather than all at once.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Brownouts occur when power supplied drops below the demand.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Blackouts occur when the grid fails completely.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Rolling blackouts (also called load shedding) are intentionally engineered electrical power outages, used to distribute insufficient power to various loads in turn.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Grid operators require reliable communications to manage the grid and associated generation and distribution facilities.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Fault-sensing protective relays at each end of the line must communicate to monitor the flow of power so that faulted conductors or equipment can be quickly de-energized and the balance of the system restored.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Protection of the transmission line from short circuits and other faults is usually so critical that common carrier telecommunications are insufficiently reliable, while in some remote areas no common carrier is available.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Rarely, and for short distances, pilot-wires are strung along the transmission line path.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Leased circuits from common carriers are not preferred since availability is not under control of the operator.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Transmission lines can be used to carry data: this is called power-line carrier, or power-line communication (PLC).
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] PLC signals can be easily received with a radio in the long wave range.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Optical fibers can be included in the stranded conductors of a transmission line, in the overhead shield wires.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] These cables are known as optical ground wire (*OPGW*).
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Sometimes a standalone cable is used, all-dielectric self-supporting (*ADSS*) cable, attached to the transmission line cross arms.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Some jurisdictions, such as Minnesota, prohibit energy transmission companies from selling surplus communication bandwidth or acting as a telecommunications common carrier.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Where the regulatory structure permits, the utility can sell capacity in extra dark fibers to a common carrier.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Electricity transmission is generally considered to be a natural monopoly, but one that is not inherently linked to generation.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Many countries regulate transmission separately from generation.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Spain was the first country to establish a regional transmission organization.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] In that country, transmission operations and electricity markets are separate.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The transmission system operator is Red Eléctrica de España (REE) and the wholesale electricity market operator is Operador del Mercado Ibérico de Energía – Polo Español, S.A.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Spain's transmission system is interconnected with those of France, Portugal, and Morocco.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The establishment of RTOs in the United States was spurred by the FERC's Order 888, *Promoting Wholesale Competition Through Open Access Non-discriminatory Transmission Services by Public Utilities; Recovery of Stranded Costs by Public Utilities and Transmitting Utilities*, issued in 1996.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] In the United States and parts of Canada, electric transmission companies operate independently of generation companies, but in the Southern United States vertical integration is intact.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] In regions of separation, transmission owners and generation owners continue to interact with each other as market participants with voting rights within their RTO.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] RTOs in the United States are regulated by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Merchant transmission projects in the United States include the Cross Sound Cable from Shoreham, New York to New Haven, Connecticut, Neptune RTS Transmission Line from Sayreville, New Jersey, to New Bridge, New York, and Path 15 in California.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Additional projects are in development or have been proposed throughout the United States, including the Lake Erie Connector, an underwater transmission line proposed by ITC Holdings Corp., connecting Ontario to load serving entities in the PJM Interconnection region.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Australia has one unregulated or market interconnector – Basslink – between Tasmania and Victoria.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Two DC links originally implemented as market interconnectors, Directlink and Murraylink, were converted to regulated interconnectors.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] A major barrier to wider adoption of merchant transmission is the difficulty in identifying who benefits from the facility so that the beneficiaries pay the toll.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Also, it is difficult for a merchant transmission line to compete when the alternative transmission lines are subsidized by utilities with a monopolized and regulated rate base.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] In the United States, the FERC's Order 1000, issued in 2010, attempted to reduce barriers to third party investment and creation of merchant transmission lines where a public policy need is found.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The cost of high voltage transmission is comparatively low, compared to all other costs constituting consumer electricity bills.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] In the UK, transmission costs are about 0.2 p per kWh compared to a delivered domestic price of around 10 p per kWh.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The level of capital expenditure in the electric power T&D equipment market was estimated to be $128.9 bn in 2011.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Mainstream scientific evidence suggests that low-power, low-frequency, electromagnetic radiation associated with household currents and high transmission power lines does not constitute a short- or long-term health hazard.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Some studies failed to find any link between living near power lines and developing any sickness or diseases, such as cancer.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] A 1997 study reported no increased risk of cancer or illness from living near a transmission line.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Other studies, however, reported statistical correlations between various diseases and living or working near power lines.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] No adverse health effects have been substantiated for people not living close to power lines.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The New York State Public Service Commission conducted a study to evaluate potential health effects of electric fields.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The study measured the electric field strength at the edge of an existing right-of-way on a 765 kV transmission line.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The field strength was 1.6 kV/m, and became the interim maximum strength standard for new transmission lines in New York State.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The opinion also limited the voltage of new transmission lines built in New York to 345 kV.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] On September 11, 1990, after a similar study of magnetic field strengths, the NYSPSC issued their *Interim Policy Statement on Magnetic Fields*.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] This policy established a magnetic field standard of 200 mG at the edge of the right-of-way using the winter-normal conductor rating.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] As a comparison with everyday items, a hair dryer or electric blanket produces a 100 mG – 500 mG magnetic field.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Applications for a new transmission line typically include an analysis of electric and magnetic field levels at the edge of rights-of-way.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Public utility commissions typically do not comment on health impacts.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Biological effects have been established for acute high level exposure to magnetic fields above 100 μT (1 G) (1,000 mG).
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] These levels exceed average residential power-frequency magnetic fields in homes, which are about 0.07 μT (0.7 mG) in Europe and 0.11 μT (1.1 mG) in North America.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] The Earth's natural geomagnetic field strength varies over the surface of the planet between 0.035 mT and 0.07 mT (35 μT – 70 μT or 350 mG – 700 mG) while the international standard for continuous exposure is set at 40 mT (400,000 mG or 400 G) for the general public.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p01] Tree growth regulators and herbicides may be used in transmission line right of ways, which may have health effects.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p02] In some countries where electric locomotives or electric multiple units run on low frequency AC power, separate single phase traction power networks are operated by the railways.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p02] Prime examples are countries such as Austria, Germany and Switzerland that utilize AC technology based on 16 2*/*3 Hz.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p02] Norway and Sweden also use this frequency but use conversion from the 50 Hz public supply; Sweden has a 16 2*/*3 Hz traction grid but only for part of the system.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p02] High-temperature superconductors (HTS) promise to revolutionize power distribution by providing lossless transmission.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p02] The development of superconductors with transition temperatures higher than the boiling point of liquid nitrogen has made the concept of superconducting power lines commercially feasible, at least for high-load applications.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p02] It has been estimated that waste would be halved using this method, since the necessary refrigeration equipment would consume about half the power saved by the elimination of resistive losses.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p02] Companies such as Consolidated Edison and American Superconductor began commercial production of such systems in 2007.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p02] Superconducting cables are particularly suited to high load density areas such as the business district of large cities, where purchase of an easement for cables is costly.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p02] Single-wire earth return (SWER) or single-wire ground return is a single-wire transmission line for supplying single-phase electrical power to remote areas at low cost.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p02] It is principally used for rural electrification, but also finds use for larger isolated loads such as water pumps.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p02] Single-wire earth return is also used for HVDC over submarine power cables.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p02] Both Nikola Tesla and Hidetsugu Yagi attempted to devise systems for large scale wireless power transmission in the late 1800s and early 1900s, without commercial success.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p02] In November 2009, LaserMotive won the NASA 2009 Power Beaming Challenge by powering a cable climber 1 km vertically using a ground-based laser transmitter.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p02] The system produced up to 1 kW of power at the receiver end.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p02] In August 2010, NASA contracted with private companies to pursue the design of laser power beaming systems to power low earth orbit satellites and to launch rockets using laser power beams.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p02] Wireless power transmission has been studied for transmission of power from solar power satellites to the earth.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p02] A high power array of microwave or laser transmitters would beam power to a rectenna.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p02] Major engineering and economic challenges face any solar power satellite project.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p02] The federal government of the United States stated that the American power grid was susceptible to cyber-warfare.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p02] The United States Department of Homeland Security works with industry to identify vulnerabilities and to help industry enhance the security of control system networks.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p02] In June 2019, Russia conceded that it was "possible" its electrical grid is under cyber-attack by the United States.
[src:transmission-distribution/electric-power-transmission-p02] *The New York Times* reported that American hackers from the United States Cyber Command planted malware potentially capable of disrupting the Russian electrical grid.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] A **substation** is a part of an electrical generation, transmission, and distribution system.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Substations transform voltage from high to low, or the reverse, or perform any of several other important functions.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Between the generating station and the consumer, electric power may flow through several substations at different voltage levels.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] A substation may include transformers to change voltage levels between high transmission voltages and lower distribution voltages, or at the interconnection of two different transmission voltages.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] They are a common component of the infrastructure.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] As of 2002, there were approximately 55,000 substations in the United States.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Substations are also occasionally known in some countries as **switchyards**.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Substations may be owned and operated by an electrical utility, or may be owned by a large industrial or commercial customer.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Generally substations are unattended, relying on SCADA for remote supervision and control.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] The word *substation* comes from the days before the distribution system became a grid.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] As central generation stations became larger, smaller generating plants were converted to distribution stations, receiving their energy supply from a larger plant instead of using their own generators.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] The first substations were connected to only one power station, where the generators were housed, and were subsidiaries of that power station.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Substations may be designed and built by a contractor or alternately all phases of its development may be handled by the electrical utility.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Most commonly, the utility does the engineering and procurement while hiring a contractor for actual construction.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Major design constraints for construction of substations include land availability and cost, limitations on the construction period, transportation restrictions, and the need to get the substation running quickly.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Prefabrication is a common way to reduce the construction cost.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] For connecting the new substation, a partial outage at another substation may be required, but the utility often tries to minimize downtime.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] A *transmission substation* connects two or more transmission lines.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] The simplest case is where all transmission lines have the same voltage.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] In such cases, substation contains high-voltage switches that allow lines to be connected or isolated for fault clearance or maintenance.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Transmission substations can range from simple to complex.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] A small "switching station" may be little more than a bus plus some circuit breakers.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] The largest transmission substations can cover a large area (several acres/hectares) with multiple voltage levels, many circuit breakers, and a large amount of protection and control equipment (voltage and current transformers, relays and SCADA systems).
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Modern substations may be implemented using international standards such as IEC Standard 61850.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] A *distribution substation* transfers power from the transmission system to the distribution system of an area.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] It is uneconomical to directly connect electricity consumers to the main transmission network, unless they use large amounts of power, so the distribution station reduces voltage to a level suitable for local distribution.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] The input for a distribution substation is typically at least two transmission or sub-transmission lines.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Input voltage may be, for example, 115 kV, or whatever is common in the area.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Distribution voltages are typically medium voltage, between 2.4 kV and 33 kV, depending on the size of the area served and the practices of the local utility.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] The feeders run along streets overhead (or underground, in some cases) and power the distribution transformers at or near the customer premises.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] In addition to transforming voltage, distribution substations also isolate faults in either the transmission or distribution systems.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Distribution substations are typically the points of voltage regulation, although on long distribution circuits (of several miles/kilometers), voltage regulation equipment may also be installed along the line.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] The downtown areas of large cities feature complicated distribution substations, with high-voltage switching, and switching and backup systems on the low-voltage side.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] More typical distribution substations have a switch, one transformer, and minimal facilities on the low-voltage side.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] In distributed generation projects such as a wind farm or photovoltaic power station, a collector substation may be required.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] It resembles a distribution substation although power flow is in the opposite direction, from many wind turbines or inverters up into the transmission grid.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Usually for economy of construction the collector system operates around 35 kV, although some collector systems are 12 kV, and the collector substation steps up voltage to a transmission voltage for the grid.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] The collector substation can also provide power factor correction if it is needed, metering, and control of the wind farm.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] In some special cases a collector substation can also contain an HVDC converter station.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Collector substations also exist where multiple thermal or hydroelectric power plants of comparable output power are in proximity.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Examples for such substations are Brauweiler in Germany and Hradec in the Czech Republic, where power is collected from nearby lignite-fired power plants.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] If no transformers are required for increasing the voltage to transmission level, the substation is a switching station.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Converter substations may be associated with HVDC converter plants, traction current, or interconnected non-synchronous networks.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] These stations contain power electronic devices to change the frequency of current, or else convert from alternating to direct current or the reverse.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Formerly rotary converters changed frequency to interconnect two systems; nowadays such substations are rare.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] A switching station is a substation without transformers and operating only at a single voltage level.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Switching stations are sometimes used as collector and distribution stations.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Sometimes they are used for switching the current to back-up lines or for parallelizing circuits in case of failure.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] An example is the switching stations for the Inga–Shaba HVDC transmission line.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] A switching station may also be known as a switchyard, and these are commonly located directly adjacent to or nearby a power station.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] In this case the generators from the power station supply their power into the yard onto the generator bus on one side of the yard, and the transmission lines take their power from a Feeder Bus on the other side of the yard.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] An important function performed by a substation is switching, which is the connecting and disconnecting of transmission lines or other components to and from the system.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Switching events may be planned or unplanned.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] A transmission line or other component may need to be de-energized for maintenance or for new construction, for example, adding or removing a transmission line or a transformer.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] To maintain reliability of supply, companies aim at keeping the system up and running while performing maintenance.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] All work to be performed, from routine testing to adding entirely new substations, should be done while keeping the whole system running.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] The function of the switching station is to isolate the faulty portion of the system in the shortest possible time.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] De-energizing faulty equipment protects it from further damage, and isolating a fault helps keep the rest of the electrical grid operating with stability.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Electrified railways also use substations, often distribution substations.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] In some cases a conversion of the current type takes place, commonly with rectifiers for direct current (DC) trains, or rotary converters for trains using alternating current (AC) at frequencies other than that of the public grid.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Sometimes they are also transmission substations or collector substations if the railway network also operates its own grid and generators to supply the other stations.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] A *mobile substation* is a substation on wheels, containing a transformer, breakers and buswork mounted on a self-contained semi-trailer, meant to be pulled by a truck.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] They are designed to be compact for travel on public roads, and are used for temporary backup in times of natural disaster or war.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Mobile substations are usually rated much lower than permanent installations, and may be built in several units to meet road travel limitations.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Substation design is aimed at minimizing cost while ensuring power availability and reliability, and enabling changes to the substation in the future.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Substations may be built outdoors, indoors, or underground or in a combination of these locations.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Selection of the location of a substation must consider many factors.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Sufficient land area is required for installation of equipment with necessary clearances for electrical safety, and for access to maintain large apparatus such as transformers.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] The site must have room for expansion due to load growth or planned transmission additions.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Environmental effects of the substation must be considered, such as drainage, noise and road traffic effects.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] The substation site must be reasonably central to the distribution area to be served.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] The site must be secure from intrusion by passers-by, both to protect people from injury by electric shock or arcs, and to protect the electrical system from misoperation due to vandalism.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] If not owned and operated by a utility company, substations are typically occupied on a long lease such as a renewable 99-year lease, giving the utility company security of tenure.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] The first step in planning a substation layout is the preparation of a single-line diagram, which shows in simplified form the switching and protection arrangement required, as well as the incoming supply lines and outgoing feeders or transmission lines.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] It is a usual practice by many electrical utilities to prepare one-line diagrams with principal elements (lines, switches, circuit breakers, transformers) arranged on the page similarly to the way the apparatus would be laid out in the actual station.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] In a common design, incoming lines have a disconnector and a circuit breaker.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] In some cases, the lines will not have both, with either a switch or a circuit breaker being all that is considered necessary.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] A disconnect switch is used to provide isolation, since it cannot interrupt load current.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] A circuit breaker is used as a protection device to interrupt fault currents automatically, and may be used to switch loads on and off, or to cut off a line when power is flowing in the 'wrong' direction.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] When a large fault current flows through the circuit breaker, this is detected through the use of current transformers.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] The magnitude of the current transformer outputs may be used to trip the circuit breaker resulting in a disconnection of the load supplied by the circuit break from the feeding point.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] This seeks to isolate the fault point from the rest of the system, and allow the rest of the system to continue operating with minimal impact.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Both switches and circuit breakers may be operated locally (within the substation) or remotely from a supervisory control center.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] With overhead transmission lines, the propagation of lightning and switching surges can cause insulation failures into substation equipment.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Line entrance surge arrestors are used to protect substation equipment accordingly.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Insulation Coordination studies are carried out extensively to ensure equipment failure (and associated outages) is minimal.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Once past the switching components, the lines of a given voltage connect to one or more buses.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] These are sets of busbars, usually in multiples of three, since three-phase electrical power distribution is largely universal around the world.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] The arrangement of switches, circuit breakers, and buses used affects the cost and reliability of the substation.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] For important substations a ring bus, double bus, or so-called "breaker and a half" setup can be used, so that the failure of any one circuit breaker does not interrupt power to other circuits, and so that parts of the substation may be de-energized for maintenance and repairs.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Substations feeding only a single industrial load may have minimal switching provisions, especially for small installations.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Because of the risk of electrical shock, substations are inherently dangerous to electrical workers.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] To mitigate this hazard, substations are designed with various safety features.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Live conductors and bare equipment are kept separate, either with protected equipment, or using screens or distance.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] To this is added the necessary space for employees to work safely and vehicles to pass.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Sometimes it is necessary to work on parts of the substation while energized, but employees must maintain a safe distance of at least 3 metres (9.8 ft).
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] The aim to reduce substation footprints comes into conflict with ease of maintenance enhanced by including gaps where employees can safely work.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Underneath a substation, a mat or grid of conductors laid around 0.5 or 0.6 metres (1 ft 8 in or 2 ft 0 in) underground provides grounding.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] This grid, which is typically copper although it may be galvanized iron in some countries, is used to ground circuits that are being worked on to prevent accidental re-energization while workers are in contact with a de-energized circuit.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Often, earth rods are driven deeper into the ground from the grounding grid for lower resistance grounding, and may be surrounded by bentonite or marconite to further reduce resistance and ensure effective grounding for the lifetime of the substation.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Above ground, the grounding conductors may be steel, aluminum, or copper.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] They must be thick enough to carry the expected current of a fault for 1–3 seconds and remain undamaged.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Substation fences, typically at least 2 metres (6 ft 7 in) in height, both protect the public from electrical hazards and also protect the substation from vandalism.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Internal fences can also be incorporated to protect employees from areas that are unsafe when energized.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Substations generally have switching, protection and control equipment, and transformers.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] In a large substation, circuit breakers are used to interrupt any short circuits or overload currents that may occur on the network.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Smaller distribution stations may use recloser circuit breakers or fuses for protection of distribution circuits.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Substations themselves do not usually have generators, although a power plant may have a substation nearby.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Other devices such as capacitors, voltage regulators, and reactors may also be located at a substation.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Substations may be on the surface in fenced enclosures, underground, or special-purpose buildings.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] High-rise buildings may have several indoor substations.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Indoor substations are usually found in urban areas to reduce the noise from transformers, improve appearance, or protect switchgear from extreme climate or pollution.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Substations often use busbars as conductors between electrical equipment.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Busbars may be aluminum tubing 3–6 inches (76–152 mm) thick, or else wires (strain bus).
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Outdoor, above-ground substation structures include wood pole, lattice metal tower, and tubular metal structures, although other variants are available.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Where space is plentiful and appearance of the station is not a factor, steel lattice towers provide low-cost supports for transmission lines and apparatus.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Low-profile substations may be specified in suburban areas where appearance is more critical.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Indoor substations may be gas insulated substations (GIS) (at high voltages, with gas insulated switchgear), or use metal-enclosed or metal-clad switchgear at lower voltages.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Urban and suburban indoor substations may be finished on the outside so as to blend in with other buildings in the area.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] A *compact substation* is generally an outdoor substation built in a metal enclosure, in which each item of the electrical equipment is located very near to each other to create a relatively smaller footprint size of the substation.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] High-voltage circuit breakers are commonly used to interrupt the flow of current in substation equipment.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] At the time of interruption, current could be normal, too high due to excessive load, unusual due to a fault, or tripped by protective relays prior to anticipated trouble.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Reclosers are similar to breakers, and can be cheaper because they do not require separate protective relays.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Often used in distribution, they often are programmed to trip when the amps exceed a certain amount over a period of time.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Reclosers will attempt to re-energize the circuit after a delay.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] If unsuccessful for a few times, the recloser will have to be manually reset by an electrical worker.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Capacitor banks are used in substations to balance the lagging current draw from inductive loads (such as motors, transformers, and some industrial equipment) with their reactive load.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Additional capacitor capacity may be needed if dispersed generation (such as small diesel generators, rooftop photovoltaic solar panels, or wind turbines) are added to the system.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Capacitors can reduce the current in wires, helping stem system losses from voltage drop or enabling extra power to be sent through the conductors.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Capacitors may be left on in response to constant inductive load or turned on when inductive load is increased, such as in the summer for air conditioners.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] The switching may be remote and can be done manually or automatically.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Larger substations have control rooms for the equipment used to monitor, control, and protect the rest of the substation equipment.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] It often contains protective relays, meters, breaker controls, communications, batteries, and recorders that save detailed data about substation operations, particularly when there is any unusual activity, to help reconstruct what happened after the fact.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] These control rooms typically are heated and air conditioned to ensure the reliable operation of this equipment.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Additional equipment is necessary to handle power surges associated with intermittent renewable energy such as dispersed generation from wind or solar.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Most transformers lose between 5 and 1.5 percent of their input as heat and noise.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Iron losses are no-load and constant whenever the transformer is energized, while copper and auxiliary losses are proportionate to the square of the current.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Auxiliary losses are due to running fans and pumps which is noisy when the transformer is operating at maximum capacity.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] To reduce noise, enclosures are often built around the transformer and can also be added after the substation is built.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Oil-based transformers are often built with bunded areas to prevent the escape of flaming or leaking oil.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Fire separation areas or firewalls are built around the transformer to stop the spread of fire.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Firefighting vehicles are allowed a path to access the area.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Maintenance of substations involves inspections, data collection and analysis, and routine scheduled work.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Using methods such as infrared scanning and dissolved gas analysis, it can be predicted when the substation will need maintenance and predict dangers before they materialize.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Infrared technology finds hot spots in the substation where electrical energy is being converted to heat, which indicates a problem and can cause additional damage from the high heat.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Dissolved gas analysis can tell when an oil-insulated transformer needs to have the oil filtered or replaced, and also detect other issues.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Early electrical substations required manual switching or adjustment of equipment, and manual collection of data for load, energy consumption, and abnormal events.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] As the complexity of distribution networks grew, it became economically necessary to automate supervision and control of substations from a centrally attended point, to allow overall coordination in case of emergencies and to reduce operating costs.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Early efforts to remote control substations used dedicated communication wires, often run alongside power circuits.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Power-line carrier, microwave radio, fiber optic cables as well as dedicated wired remote control circuits have all been applied to Supervisory Control and Data Acquisition (SCADA) for substations.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] The development of the microprocessor made for an exponential increase in the number of points that could be economically controlled and monitored.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Today, standardized communication protocols such as DNP3, IEC 61850 and Modbus, to list a few, are used to allow multiple intelligent electronic devices to communicate with each other and supervisory control centers.
[src:transmission-distribution/electrical-substation] Distributed automatic control at substations is one element of the so-called smart grid.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] A **high-voltage direct current** (**HVDC**) system uses direct current (DC) and high voltages (currently between 100 kV and 800 kV) for electric power transmission.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] It contrasts with the more common alternating current (AC) transmission systems.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] HVDC lines are commonly used for long-distance power transmission, since they require fewer conductors and incur less power loss than equivalent AC lines.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] HVDC also allows power transmission between AC transmission systems that are not synchronized.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Since the power flow through an HVDC link can be controlled independently of the phase angle between source and load, it can stabilize a network against disturbances due to rapid changes in power.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] HVDC also allows the transfer of power between grid systems running at different frequencies, such as 50 and 60 Hz.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] This improves the stability and economy of each grid, by allowing the exchange of power between previously incompatible networks.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The modern form of HVDC transmission uses technology developed extensively in the 1930s in Sweden (ASEA) and in Germany.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Early commercial installations included one in the Soviet Union in 1951 between Moscow and Kashira, and a 100 kV, 20 MW system between Gotland and mainland Sweden in 1954.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The longest HVDC link in the world is the Zhundong–South Anhui link in China, a ±1,100 kV, ultra HVDC line with a length of more than 3,000 km (1,900 mi).
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] High voltage is used for electric power transmission to reduce the energy lost in the resistance of the wires.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Since the energy lost as heat in the wires is directly proportional to the square of the current ${\textstyle ({\text{energy lost as heat}}={\text{current}}^{2}\cdot {\text{resistance}}\cdot {\text{time}}),}$ using half the current at double the voltage reduces the line losses by a factor of 4.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] While energy lost in transmission can also be reduced by decreasing the resistance by increasing the conductor size, larger conductors are heavier and more expensive.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] High voltage cannot readily be used for lighting or motors, so transmission-level voltages must be reduced for end-use equipment.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Transformers are used to change the voltage levels in alternating current (AC) transmission circuits, but cannot pass DC current.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Transformers make AC voltage changes practical, and AC generators are more efficient than those using DC.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] These advantages led to early low-voltage DC transmission systems being supplanted by AC systems around the turn of the 20th century.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The first long-distance transmission of electric power was demonstrated using direct current in 1882 in the 57 km Miesbach-Munich Power Transmission, but only 1.5 kW was transmitted.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] An early method of HVDC transmission was developed by the Swiss engineer René Thury and his method, the Thury system, was put into practice by 1889 in Italy by the Acquedotto De Ferrari-Galliera company.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] This system used series-connected motor-generator sets to increase the voltage.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Each set was insulated from electrical ground and driven by insulated shafts from a prime mover.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The transmission line was operated in a constant-current mode, with up to 5,000 volts across each machine, some machines having double commutators to reduce the voltage on each commutator.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] This system transmitted 630 kW at 14 kV DC over a distance of 120 kilometres (75 mi).
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The Moutiers–Lyon system transmitted 8,600 kW of hydroelectric power a distance of 200 kilometres (120 mi), including 10 kilometres (6.2 mi) of underground cable.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] This system used eight series-connected generators with dual commutators for a total voltage of 150 kV between the positive and negative poles, and operated from c.1906 until 1936.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Fifteen Thury systems were in operation by 1913.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Other Thury systems operating at up to 100 kV DC worked into the 1930s, but the rotating machinery required high maintenance and had high energy loss.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Various other electromechanical devices were tested during the first half of the 20th century with little commercial success.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] One technique attempted for conversion of direct current from a high transmission voltage to lower utilization voltage was to charge series-connected batteries, then reconnect the batteries in parallel to serve distribution loads.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] First proposed in 1914, the grid controlled mercury-arc valve became available during the period 1920 to 1940 for the rectifier and inverter functions associated with DC transmission.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Starting in 1932, General Electric tested mercury-vapor valves and a 12 kV DC transmission line, which also served to convert 40 Hz generation to serve 60 Hz loads, at Mechanicville, New York.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] In 1941, a 60 MW, ±200 kV, 115 km (71 mi) buried cable link, known as the Elbe-Project, was designed for the city of Berlin using mercury arc valves but, owing to the collapse of the German government in 1945, the project was never completed.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The nominal justification for the project was that, during wartime, a buried cable would be less conspicuous as a bombing target.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The equipment was moved to the Soviet Union and was put into service there as the Moscow–Kashira HVDC system.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The Moscow–Kashira system and the 1954 connection by Uno Lamm's group at ASEA between the mainland of Sweden and the island of Gotland marked the beginning of the modern era of HVDC transmission.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Mercury arc valves were common in systems designed up to 1972, the last mercury arc HVDC system (the Nelson River Bipole 1 system in Manitoba, Canada) having been put into service in stages between 1972 and 1977.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Since then, all mercury arc systems have been either shut down or converted to use solid-state devices.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The last HVDC system to use mercury arc valves was the Inter-Island HVDC link between the North and South Islands of New Zealand, which used them on one of its two poles.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The mercury arc valves were decommissioned on 1 August 2012, ahead of the commissioning of replacement thyristor converters.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The development of thyristor valves for HVDC began in the late 1960s.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The first complete HVDC scheme based on thyristor was the Eel River scheme in Canada, which was built by General Electric and went into service in 1972.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Since 1977, new HVDC systems have used solid-state devices, in most cases thyristors.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Like mercury arc valves, thyristors require connection to an external AC circuit in HVDC applications to turn them on and off.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] HVDC using thyristors is also known as *line-commutated converter* (LCC) HVDC.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] On March 15, 1979, a 1920 MW thyristor based direct current connection between Cabora Bassa and Johannesburg (1,410 km; 880 mi) was energized.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The conversion equipment was built in 1974 by Allgemeine Elektricitäts-Gesellschaft AG (AEG), and Brown, Boveri & Cie (BBC) and Siemens were partners in the project.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Service interruptions of several years were a result of a civil war in Mozambique.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The transmission voltage of ±533 kV was the highest in the world at the time.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Line-commutated converters have some limitations in their use for HVDC systems.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] This results from requiring a period of *reverse* voltage to affect the turn off.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] An attempt to address these limitations is the capacitor-commutated converter (CCC).
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The CCC has series capacitors inserted into the AC line connections.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] CCC has remained only a niche application because of the advent of voltage-source converters (VSCs) which more directly address turn-off issues.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Widely used in motor drives since the 1980s, voltage-source converters (VSCs) started to appear in HVDC in 1997 with the experimental Hellsjön–Grängesberg project in Sweden.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] By the end of 2011, this technology had captured a significant proportion of the HVDC market.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The development of higher rated insulated-gate bipolar transistors (IGBTs), gate turn-off thyristors (GTOs), and integrated gate-commutated thyristors (IGCTs), has made HVDC systems more economical and reliable.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] This is because modern IGBTs incorporate a short-circuit failure mode, wherein should an IGBT fail, it is mechanically shorted.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Therefore, modern VSC HVDC converter stations are designed with sufficient redundancy to guarantee operation over their entire service lives.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] They have extended the use of HVDC down to blocks as small as a few tens of megawatts and overhead lines as short as a few dozen kilometers.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] There are several different variants of VSC technology: most installations built until 2012 use pulse-width modulation in a circuit that is effectively an ultra-high-voltage motor drive.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] More recent installations, including HVDC PLUS and HVDC MaxSine, are based on variants of a converter called a *modular multilevel converter* (MMC).
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Multilevel converters have the advantage that they allow harmonic filtering equipment to be reduced or eliminated altogether.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] By way of comparison, AC harmonic filters of typical line-commutated converter stations cover nearly half of the converter station area.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] With time, voltage-source converter systems will probably replace all installed simple thyristor-based systems, including the highest DC power transmission applications.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] A long-distance, point-to-point HVDC transmission scheme generally has lower overall investment cost and lower losses than an equivalent AC transmission scheme.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Although HVDC conversion equipment at the terminal stations is costly, the total DC transmission-line costs over long distances are lower than for an AC line of the same distance.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] HVDC requires less conductor per unit distance than an AC line, as there is no need to support three phases and there is no skin effect.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] AC systems use a higher peak voltage for the same power, increasing insulator costs.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Depending on voltage level and construction details, HVDC transmission losses are quoted at 3.5% per 1,000 km (620 mi), about 50% less than AC (6.7%) lines at the same voltage.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] This is because direct current transfers only active power and thus causes lower losses than alternating current, which transfers both active and reactive power.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] In other words, transmitting electric AC power over long distances inevitably results in a phase shift between voltage and current.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Because of this phase shift the effective Power = Current × Voltage, where × designates a vector product, decreases.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Since DC power has no phase, the phase shift cannot occur in the DC case.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] In addition HVDC is particularly useful for submarine cables.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] With submarine AC cables, induction and capacitance with the surrounding sea water causes larger than normal losses, which HVDC lacks, and so HVDC submarine cables can be much longer.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] HVDC transmission may also be selected for other technical benefits.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] HVDC can transfer power between separate AC networks.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] HVDC power flow between separate AC systems can be automatically controlled to support either network during transient conditions, but without the risk that a major power-system collapse in one network will lead to a collapse in the second.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The controllability feature is also useful where control of energy trading is needed.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Long undersea or underground high-voltage cables have a high electrical capacitance compared with overhead transmission lines since the live conductors within the cable are surrounded by a relatively thin layer of insulation (the dielectric), and a metal sheath.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The geometry is that of a long coaxial capacitor.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The total capacitance increases with the length of the cable.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] This capacitance is in a parallel circuit with the load.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Where alternating current is used for cable transmission, additional current must flow in the cable to charge this cable capacitance.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Another way to look at this is to realize, that such capacitance causes a phase shift between voltage and current, and thus decrease of the transmitted power, which is a vector product of voltage and current.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Additional energy losses also occur as a result of dielectric losses in the cable insulation.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] For a sufficiently long AC cable, the entire current-carrying ability of the conductor would be needed to supply the charging current alone.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] This cable capacitance issue limits the length and power-carrying ability of AC power cables.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] However, if direct current is used, the cable capacitance is charged only when the cable is first energized or if the voltage level changes; there is no additional current required.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] DC powered cables are limited only by their temperature rise and Ohm's law.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Although some leakage current flows *through* the dielectric insulator, this effect is also present in AC systems and is small compared to the cable's rated current.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The capacitive effect of long underground or undersea cables in AC transmission applications also applies to AC overhead lines, although to a much lesser extent.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Nevertheless, for a long AC overhead transmission line, the current flowing just to charge the line capacitance can be significant, and this reduces the capability of the line to carry useful current to the load at the remote end.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Another factor that reduces the useful current-carrying ability of AC lines is the skin effect, which causes a nonuniform distribution of current over the cross-sectional area of the conductor.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Transmission line conductors operating with direct current suffer from neither constraint.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Therefore, for the same conductor losses (or heating effect), a given conductor can carry more power to the load when operating with HVDC than AC.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The power delivered in an AC system is defined by the root mean square (RMS) of an AC voltage, but RMS is only about 71% of the peak voltage.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Because HVDC allows power transmission between unsynchronized AC distribution systems, it can help increase system stability, by preventing cascading failures from propagating from one part of a wider power transmission grid to another.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Changes in load that would cause portions of an AC network to become unsynchronized and to separate, would not similarly affect a DC link, and the power flow through the DC link would tend to stabilize the AC network.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The magnitude and direction of power flow through a DC link can be directly controlled and changed as needed to support the AC networks at either end of the DC link.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The disadvantages of HVDC are in conversion, switching, control, availability, and maintenance.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] HVDC is less reliable and has lower availability than alternating current (AC) systems, mainly due to the extra conversion equipment.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Single-pole systems have availability of about 98.5%, with about a third of the downtime unscheduled due to faults.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Fault-tolerant bipole systems provide high availability for 50% of the link capacity, but availability of the full capacity is about 97% to 98%.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The required converter stations are expensive and have limited overload capacity.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] At smaller transmission distances, the losses in the converter stations may be bigger than in an AC transmission line for the same distance.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The cost of the converters may not be offset by reductions in line construction cost and power line loss.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Operating an HVDC scheme requires many spare parts to be kept, often exclusively for one system, as HVDC systems are less standardized than AC systems and technology changes more quickly.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] In contrast to AC systems, realizing multi-terminal systems is complex (especially with line commutated converters), as is expanding existing schemes to multi-terminal systems.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Controlling power flow in a multi-terminal DC system requires good communication between all the terminals; power flow must be actively regulated by the converter control system instead of relying on the inherent impedance and phase angle properties of an AC transmission line.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Multi-terminal systems are therefore rare.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] As of 2012 only two are in service: the Quebec – New England Transmission between Radisson, Nicolet and Sandy Pond and the Sardinia–mainland Italy link which was modified in 1989 to also provide power to the island of Corsica.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] HVDC circuit breakers are difficult to build because of arcing: under AC, the voltage inverts and in doing so crosses zero volts dozens of times a second.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] An AC arc will self-extinguish at one of these zero-crossing points because there cannot be an arc where there is no potential difference.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] DC will never cross zero volts and never self-extinguish, so arc distance and duration is far greater with DC than the same voltage AC.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] This means some mechanism must be included in the circuit breaker to force current to zero and extinguish the arc, otherwise arcing and contact wear would be too great to allow reliable switching.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] In November 2012, ABB announced the first ultrafast HVDC circuit breaker.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Mechanical circuit breakers are too slow for use in HVDC grids, although they have been used for years in other applications.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Conversely, semiconductor breakers are fast enough but have a high resistance when conducting, wasting energy and generating heat in normal operation.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The ABB breaker combines semiconductor and mechanical breakers to produce a *hybrid breaker* with both a fast break time and a low resistance in normal operation.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] An April 2010 announcement for a 2,000 MW, 64 km (40 mi) line between Spain and France is estimated at €700 million.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] This includes the cost of a tunnel through the Pyrenees.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] At the heart of an HVDC converter station, the equipment that performs the conversion between AC and DC is referred to as the *converter*.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Almost all HVDC converters are inherently capable of converting from AC to DC (*rectification*) and from DC to AC (*inversion*), although in many HVDC systems, the system as a whole is optimized for power flow in only one direction.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Irrespective of how the converter itself is designed, the station that is operating (at a given time) with power flow from AC to DC is referred to as the *rectifier* and the station that is operating with power flow from DC to AC is referred to as the *inverter*.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Early HVDC systems used electromechanical conversion (the Thury system), but all HVDC systems built since the 1940s have used electronic converters.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Most of the HVDC systems in operation today are based on line-commutated converters (LCCs).
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The basic LCC configuration uses a three-phase bridge rectifier known as a *six-pulse bridge*, containing six electronic switches, each connecting one of the three phases to one of the two DC rails.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] A complete switching element is usually referred to as a *valve*, irrespective of its construction.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] However, with a phase change only every 60°, considerable harmonic distortion is produced at both the DC and AC terminals when this arrangement is used.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] An enhancement of this arrangement uses 12 valves in a *twelve-pulse bridge*.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The AC is split into two separate three-phase supplies before transformation.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] One of the sets of supplies is then configured to have a star (wye) secondary, and the other a delta secondary, establishing a 30° phase difference between the two sets of three phases.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] With twelve valves connecting each of the two sets of three phases to the two DC rails, there is a phase change every 30°, and harmonics are considerably reduced.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] For this reason, the twelve-pulse system has become standard on most line-commutated converter HVDC systems built since the 1970s.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] With line commutated converters, the converter has only one degree of freedom – the *firing angle*, which represents the time delay between the voltage across a valve becoming positive (at which point the valve would start to conduct if it were made from diodes) and the thyristors being turned on.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The DC output voltage of the converter steadily becomes less positive as the firing angle is increased: firing angles of up to 90° correspond to rectification and result in positive DC voltages, while firing angles above 90° correspond to inversion and result in negative DC voltages.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The practical upper limit for the firing angle is about 150–160° because above this, the valve would have insufficient turnoff time.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Early LCC systems used mercury-arc valves, which were rugged but required high maintenance.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Because of this, many mercury-arc HVDC systems were built with bypass switchgear across each six-pulse bridge so that the HVDC scheme could be operated in six-pulse mode for short maintenance periods.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The last mercury arc system, at the HVDC Inter-Island link, was decommissioned on 1 August 2012.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The thyristor valve was first used in HVDC systems in 1972.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The thyristor is a solid-state semiconductor device similar to the diode, but with an extra control terminal that is used to switch the device on at a particular instant during the AC cycle.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Because the voltages in HVDC systems, up to 800 kV in some cases, far exceed the breakdown voltages of the thyristors used, HVDC thyristor valves are built using large numbers of thyristors in series.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Additional passive components such as grading capacitors and resistors need to be connected in parallel with each thyristor in order to ensure that the voltage across the valve is evenly shared between the thyristors.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The thyristor plus its grading circuits and other auxiliary equipment is known as a *thyristor level*.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Each thyristor valve will typically contain tens or hundreds of thyristor levels, each operating at a different (high) potential with respect to earth.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The command information to turn on the thyristors therefore cannot simply be sent using a wire connection – it needs to be isolated.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The isolation method can be magnetic but is usually optical.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Two optical methods are used: indirect and direct optical triggering.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] In the indirect optical triggering method, low-voltage control electronics send light pulses along optical fibers to the *high-side* control electronics, which derives its power from the voltage across each thyristor.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The alternative direct optical triggering method dispenses with most of the high-side electronics, instead using light pulses from the control electronics to switch light-triggered thyristors (LTTs).
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] In a line-commutated converter, the DC current (usually) cannot change direction; it flows through a large inductance and can be considered almost constant.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] On the AC side, the converter behaves approximately as a current source, injecting both grid-frequency and harmonic currents into the AC network.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] For this reason, a line-commutated converter for HVDC is also considered as a *current-source inverter*.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Because thyristors can only be turned on (not off) by control action, the control system has only one degree of freedom – when to turn on the thyristor.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] This is an important limitation in some circumstances.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] With some other types of semiconductor devices such as the insulated-gate bipolar transistor (IGBT), both turn-on and turn-off can be controlled, giving a second degree of freedom.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] As a result, they can be used to make *self-commutated converters*.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] In such converters, the electric polarity of DC voltage is usually fixed and the DC voltage, being smoothed by a large capacitance, can be considered constant.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] For this reason, an HVDC converter using IGBTs is usually referred to as a *voltage-sourced converter*.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The additional controllability gives many advantages, notably the ability to switch the IGBTs on and off many times per cycle in order to improve the harmonic performance.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Being self-commutated, the converter no longer relies on synchronous machines in the AC system for its operation.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] A voltage-sourced converter can therefore feed power to an AC network consisting only of passive loads, something which is impossible with LCC HVDC.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] HVDC systems based on voltage-sourced converters normally use the six-pulse connection because the converter produces much less harmonic distortion than a comparable LCC and the twelve-pulse connection is unnecessary.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Most of the VSC HVDC systems built until 2012 were based on the *two-level converter*, which can be thought of as a six-pulse bridge in which the thyristors have been replaced by IGBTs with inverse-parallel diodes and the DC smoothing reactors have been replaced by DC smoothing capacitors.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Such converters derive their name from the discrete, two voltage levels at the AC output of each phase that correspond to the electrical potentials of the positive and negative DC terminals.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Pulse-width modulation (PWM) is usually used to improve the harmonic distortion of the converter.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The IGBTs in each submodule either bypass the capacitor or connect it into the circuit, allowing the valve to synthesize a stepped voltage with very low levels of harmonic distortion.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] At the AC side of each converter, transformers—often a bank of three single-phase transformers—isolate the station from the AC supply to provide a local earth and to achieve the correct DC voltage.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Converter transformers for LCC HVDC schemes are quite specialized because of the high levels of harmonic currents that flow through them, and because the secondary winding insulation experiences a permanent DC voltage, which affects the design of the insulating structure inside the tank.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] In LCC systems, the transformers also need to provide the 30° phase shift required for harmonic cancellation.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Converter transformers for VSC HVDC systems are usually simpler and more conventional in design than those for LCC HVDC systems.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] A major drawback of HVDC systems using line-commutated converters is that the converters inherently consume reactive power.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The AC current flowing into the converter from the AC system lags behind the AC voltage so that, irrespective of the direction of active power flow, the converter always absorbs reactive power, behaving in the same way as a shunt reactor.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The reactive power absorbed is at least 0.5 Mvar/MW under ideal conditions and can be higher than this when the converter is operating at higher than usual firing or extinction angle, or reduced DC voltage.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Although at HVDC converter stations connected directly to power stations some of the reactive power may be provided by the generators themselves, in most cases the reactive power consumed by the converter must be provided by banks of shunt capacitors connected at the AC terminals of the converter.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The shunt capacitors are usually connected directly to the grid voltage but in some cases may be connected to a lower voltage via a tertiary winding on the converter transformer.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Since the reactive power consumed depends on the active power being transmitted, the shunt capacitors usually need to be subdivided into a number of switchable banks (typically four per converter) in order to prevent a surplus of reactive power being generated at low transmitted power.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The shunt capacitors are almost always provided with tuning reactors and, where necessary, damping resistors so that they can perform a dual role as harmonic filters.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] VSCs, on the other hand, can either produce or consume reactive power on demand, with the result that usually no separate shunt capacitors are needed (other than those required purely for filtering).
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] All electronic power converters generate some degree of harmonic distortion on the AC and DC systems to which they are connected, and HVDC converters are no exception.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] With the recently developed MMCs, levels of harmonic distortion may be practically negligible, but with line-commutated converters and simpler types of VSCs, considerable harmonic distortion may be produced on both the AC and DC sides of the converter.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] As a result, harmonic filters are nearly always required at the AC terminals of such converters, and in HVDC transmission schemes using overhead lines, may also be required on the DC side.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The basic building block of a line-commutated HVDC converter is the *six-pulse bridge*.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] This arrangement produces very high levels of harmonic distortion.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] It is very costly to provide harmonic filters capable of suppressing such harmonics, so a variant known as the *twelve-pulse bridge*, consisting of two six-pulse bridges in series with a 30° phase shift between them, is nearly always used.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The task of suppressing harmonics from this arrangement is still challenging, but manageable.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Line-commutated converters for HVDC are usually include combinations of harmonic filters designed to deal with the 11th and 13th harmonics on the AC side, and 12th harmonic on the DC side.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Sometimes, high-pass filters are included to deal with 23rd, 25th, 35th, 37th... on the AC side and 24th, 36th... on the DC side.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Sometimes, the AC filters provide damping at lower-order, *noncharacteristic* harmonics such as 3rd or 5th harmonics.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Detailed knowledge of the *harmonic impedance* of the AC system, at a wide range of frequencies, is needed in order to design the AC filters.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] DC filters are required only for HVDC transmission systems involving overhead lines.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] With the rise in digital mobile telecommunications systems, which are much less susceptible to this type of interference, and fiber optic communication which is immune, DC filters are becoming less important for HVDC systems.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Some types of voltage-sourced converters may produce such low levels of harmonic distortion that no filters are required.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] However, converter types such as the *two-level* converter, used with pulse-width modulation (PWM), still require some filtering, albeit less than on line-commutated converter systems.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] In two-level converters, the harmonic spectrum is shifted to higher frequencies compared to line-commutated converters.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The dominant harmonic frequencies are sidebands of the PWM frequency and multiples thereof.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] In HVDC applications, the PWM frequency is typically around 1 to 2 kHz.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The higher frequencies allow the filter equipment to be smaller.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] In a monopole configuration, one of the terminals of the rectifier is connected to earth ground using an electrode.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The other terminal, at high voltage relative to ground, is connected to a transmission line.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] With no metallic return conductor installed, return current flows in the earth (or water) between two stations.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] This arrangement is a type of single-wire earth return system.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The electrodes are usually located some tens of kilometers from the stations and are connected to the stations via a medium-voltage electrode line.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The design of the electrodes themselves depends on whether they are located on land, on the shore or at sea.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] For the monopolar configuration with earth return, the earth current flow is unidirectional, which means that the design of one of the electrodes (the cathode) can be relatively simple, although the design of anode electrode is quite complex due to corrosion issues associated with electrochemistry.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] These effects can be eliminated with the installation of a metallic return conductor between the two ends of the monopolar transmission line.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Since one terminal of the converters is connected to earth, the return conductor need not be insulated for the full transmission voltage, which makes it less costly than the high-voltage conductor.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The decision of whether or not to use a metallic return conductor is based upon economic, technical and environmental factors.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Modern monopolar systems for pure overhead lines typically carry 2 GW.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] If underground or underwater cables are used, the typical value is 1 GW.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Most monopolar systems are designed for future bipolar expansion.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Transmission line towers may be designed to carry two conductors, even if only one is used initially for the monopole transmission system.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The second conductor is either unused, used as electrode line or connected in parallel with the other (as in case of Baltic Cable).
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] An alternative is to use two high-voltage conductors, operating at about half of the DC voltage, with only a single converter at each end.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] In this arrangement, known as the *symmetrical monopole*, the converters are earthed only via a high impedance and there is no earth current.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The symmetrical monopole arrangement is uncommon with line-commutated converters (the NorNed interconnector being a rare example) but is very common with voltage-sourced converters when cables are used.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] In bipolar transmission, a pair of conductors is used, each at a high potential with respect to ground, in opposite polarity.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Since these conductors must be insulated for the full voltage, the transmission line cost is higher than a monopole with a return conductor.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Bipolar systems may carry as much as 4 GW at voltages of ±660 kV with a single converter per pole, as on the Ningdong–Shandong project in China.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] With a power rating of 2 GW per twelve-pulse converter, the converters for that project were, as of 2010, the most powerful HVDC converters ever built.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Even higher powers can be achieved by connecting two or more twelve-pulse converters in series in each pole, as is done in the ±800 kV Xiangjiaba–Shanghai project in China, which uses two twelve-pulse converter bridges in each pole, each rated at 400 kV DC and 1.6 GW.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Submarine cable installations initially commissioned as a monopole may be upgraded with additional cables and operated as a bipole.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] A bipolar scheme can be implemented so that the polarity of one or both poles can be changed.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] This allows operation as two parallel monopoles, so if one conductor fails, transmission can still continue at reduced capacity.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Losses may increase if ground electrodes and lines are not designed for the extra current in this mode.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] To reduce losses in this case, intermediate switching stations may be installed, at which line segments can be switched off or parallelized.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] This configuration was implemented at Inga–Shaba HVDC.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] A **back-to-back station** (**B2B**) is a plant in which both converters are in the same area, usually in the same building.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The length of the direct current line is kept as short as possible.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The DC voltage in the intermediate circuit can be selected freely at back-to-back stations because of the short conductor length.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The DC voltage is usually selected to be as low as possible, in order to build a small valve hall and to reduce the number of thyristors connected in series in each valve.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] For this reason, at HVDC back-to-back stations, valves with the highest available current rating (in some cases, up to 4,500 A) are used.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The most common configuration of an HVDC link consists of two converter stations connected by an overhead power line or undersea cable.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Multi-terminal HVDC links, connecting more than two points, are rare.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The configuration of multiple terminals can be series, parallel, or hybrid (a mixture of series and parallel).
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Parallel configuration tends to be used for large-capacity stations, and series for lower-capacity stations.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] An example is the 2,000 MW Quebec - New England Transmission system opened in 1992.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] When it opened in 1992, it was the largest multi-terminal HVDC system in the world.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Multi-terminal systems are difficult to realize using line-commutated converters because reversals of power are effected by reversing the polarity of DC voltage, which affects all converters connected to the system.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] With voltage-sourced converters, power reversal is achieved instead by reversing the direction of current, making parallel-connected multi-terminal systems much easier to control.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] While addressing environmental targets, China is expanding its grid to keep up with increased power demand.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] China Southern Power Grid started a three-terminal VSC HVDC pilot project in 2011.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The project has designed ratings of ±160 kV at 200 MW-100 MW-50 MW and will be used to bring wind power generated on Nanao island into the mainland Guangdong power grid through 32 km (20 mi) of combination of HVDC land cables, sea cables and overhead lines.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] This project was put into operation on December 19, 2013.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] In India, the multi-terminal North-East Agra project is planned for commissioning in 2015–2017.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] It is rated 6,000 MW, and it transmits power on a ±800 kV bipolar line from two converter stations, at Biswanath Chariali and Alipurduar, in the east to a converter at Agra, a distance of 1,728 km (1,074 mi).
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Cross-Skagerrak consisted since 1993 of three poles, from which two were switched in parallel and the third used an opposite polarity with a higher transmission voltage.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] This configuration ended in 2014 when poles 1 and 2 again were rebuilt to work in bipole and pole 3 (LCC) works in bipole with a new pole 4 (VSC).
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] This is the first HVDC transmission where LCC and VSC poles cooperate in a bipole.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] This configuration ended in 2012 when the two old converters were replaced with a single, new, thyristor converter.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] A scheme patented in 2004 is intended for conversion of existing AC transmission lines to HVDC.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Two of the three circuit conductors are operated as a bipole.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The third conductor is used as a parallel monopole, equipped with reversing valves (or parallel valves connected in reverse polarity).
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] This allows heavier currents to be carried by the bipole conductors, and full use of the installed third conductor for energy transmission.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] High currents can be circulated through the line conductors even when load demand is low, for removal of ice.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] As of 2012, no tripole conversions are in operation, although a transmission line in India has been converted to bipole HVDC (HVDC Sileru-Barsoor).
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Corona discharge is the creation of ions in a fluid (such as air) by the presence of a strong electric field.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Electrons are torn from neutral air, and either the positive ions or the electrons are attracted to the conductor, while the charged particles drift.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] This effect can cause considerable power loss, create audible and radio-frequency interference, generate toxic compounds such as oxides of nitrogen and ozone, and bring forth arcing.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Both AC and DC transmission lines can generate coronas, in the former case in the form of oscillating particles, in the latter a constant wind.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Due to the space charge formed around the conductors, an HVDC system may have about half the loss per unit length of a high voltage AC system carrying the same amount of power.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] With monopolar transmission the choice of polarity of the energized conductor leads to a degree of control over the corona discharge.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] In particular, the polarity of the ions emitted can be controlled, which may have an environmental impact on ozone creation.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] Negative coronas generate considerably more ozone than positive coronas, and generate it further *downwind* of the power line, creating the potential for health effects.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p01] The use of a *positive* voltage will reduce the ozone impacts of monopole HVDC power lines.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p02] Offshore windfarms also require undersea cables, and their turbines are unsynchronized.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p02] In very long-distance connections between two locations, such as power transmission from a large hydroelectric power plant at a remote site to an urban area, HVDC transmission systems may appropriately be used; several schemes of these kind have been built.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p02] For interconnectors to Siberia, Canada, India, and the Scandinavian North, the decreased line-costs of HVDC also make it applicable, see List of HVDC projects.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p02] Other applications are noted throughout this article.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p02] AC transmission lines can interconnect only synchronized AC networks with the same frequency with limits on the allowable phase difference between the two ends of the line.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p02] Many areas that wish to share power have unsynchronized networks.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p02] The power grids of the UK, Northern Europe and continental Europe are not united into a single synchronized network.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p02] Continental North America, while operating at 60 Hz throughout, is divided into regions which are unsynchronized: East, West, Texas, Quebec, and Alaska.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p02] Brazil and Paraguay, which share the enormous Itaipu Dam hydroelectric plant, operate on 60 Hz and 50 Hz respectively.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p02] However, HVDC systems make it possible to interconnect unsynchronized AC networks, and also add the possibility of controlling AC voltage and reactive power flow.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p02] A generator connected to a long AC transmission line may become unstable and fall out of synchronization with a distant AC power system.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p02] An HVDC transmission link may make it economically feasible to use remote generation sites.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p02] Wind farms located off-shore may use HVDC systems to collect power from multiple unsynchronized generators for transmission to the shore by an underwater cable.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p02] In general, however, an HVDC power line will interconnect two AC regions of the power-distribution grid.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p02] Machinery to convert between AC and DC power adds a considerable cost in power transmission.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p02] The conversion from AC to DC is known as rectification, and from DC to AC as inversion.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p02] Above a certain break-even distance (about 50 km; 31 mi for submarine cables, and perhaps 600–800 km; 370–500 mi for overhead cables), the lower cost of the HVDC electrical conductors outweighs the cost of the electronics.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p02] The conversion electronics also present an opportunity to effectively manage the power grid by means of controlling the magnitude and direction of power flow.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p02] An additional advantage of the existence of HVDC links, therefore, is potential increased stability in the transmission grid.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p02] A number of studies have highlighted the potential benefits of very wide area super grids based on HVDC since they can mitigate the effects of intermittency by averaging and smoothing the outputs of large numbers of geographically dispersed wind farms or solar farms.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p02] Czisch's study concludes that a grid covering the fringes of Europe could bring 100% renewable power (70% wind, 30% biomass) at close to today's prices.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p02] There has been debate over the technical feasibility of this proposal and the political risks involved in energy transmission across a large number of international borders.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p02] The construction of such green power superhighways is advocated in a white paper that was released by the American Wind Energy Association and the Solar Energy Industries Association in 2009.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p02] Clean Line Energy Partners is developing four HVDC lines in the US for long-distance electric power transmission.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p02] Meanwhile, the recently founded Union of the Mediterranean has embraced a Mediterranean Solar Plan to import large amounts of concentrated solar power into Europe from North Africa and the Middle East.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p02] Japan-Taiwan-Philippines HVDC interconnector was proposed in 2020.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p02] The purpose of this interconnector is to facilitate cross-border renewable power trading with Indonesia and Australia, in preparation for the future Asian Pacific Super Grid.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p02] UHVDC (ultrahigh-voltage direct-current) is shaping up to be the latest technological front in high voltage DC transmission technology.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p02] UHVDC is defined as DC voltage transmission of above 800 kV (HVDC is generally just 100 to 800 kV).
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p02] One of the problems with current UHVDC supergrids is that – although less than AC transmission or DC transmission at lower voltages – they still suffer from power loss as the length is extended.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p02] A typical loss for 800 kV lines is 2.6% over 800 km (500 mi).
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p02] Increasing the transmission voltage on such lines reduces the power loss, but until recently, the interconnectors required to bridge the segments were prohibitively expensive.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p02] However, with advances in manufacturing, it is becoming more and more feasible to build UHVDC lines.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p02] In 2010, ABB built the world's first 800 kV UHVDC in China.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p02] The Zhundong–Wannan UHVDC line with 1100 kV, 3,400 km (2,100 mi) length and 12 GW capacity was completed in 2018.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p02] As of 2020, at least thirteen UHVDC transmission lines in China have been completed.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p02] While the majority of recent UHVDC technology deployment is in China, it has also been deployed in South America as well as other parts of Asia.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p02] In India, a 1,830 km (1,140 mi), 800 kV, 6 GW line between Raigarh and Pugalur was expected to be completed in 2019.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p02] In Brazil, the Xingu-Estreito line over 2,076 km (1,290 mi) with 800 kV and 4 GW was completed in 2017, and the Xingu-Rio line over 2,543 km (1,580 mi) with 800 kV and 4 GW was completed in 2019, both to transmit the energy from Belo Monte Dam.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p02] As of 2020, no UHVDC line (≥ 800 kV) exists in Europe or North America.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p02] A 1,100 kV link in China was completed in 2019 over a distance of 3,300 km (2,100 mi) with a power capacity of 12 GW.
[src:transmission-distribution/high-voltage-direct-current-p02] With this dimension, intercontinental connections become possible which could help to deal with the fluctuations of wind power and photovoltaics.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] An **overhead power line** is a structure used in electric power transmission and distribution to transmit electrical energy along large distances.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] It consists of one or more conductors (commonly multiples of three) suspended by towers or poles.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Since the surrounding air provides good cooling and insulation along long passages and allows optical inspection, overhead power lines are generally the lowest-cost method of power transmission for large quantities of electric energy.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Towers for support of the lines are made of wood (as-grown or laminated), steel or aluminum (either lattice structures or tubular poles), concrete, and occasionally reinforced plastics.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] The bare wire conductors on the line are generally made of aluminum (either plain or reinforced with steel, or composite materials such as carbon and glass fiber), though some copper wires are used in medium-voltage distribution and low-voltage connections to customer premises.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Today, some overhead lines are routinely operated at voltages exceeding 765,000 volts between conductors, with even higher voltages possible in some cases.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Structures for overhead lines take a variety of shapes depending on the type of line.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Structures may be as simple as wood poles directly set in the earth, carrying one or more cross-arm beams to support conductors, or "armless" construction with conductors supported on insulators attached to the side of the pole.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Tubular steel poles are typically used in urban areas.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] High-voltage lines are often carried on lattice-type steel towers or pylons.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] For remote areas, aluminum towers may be placed by helicopters.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Poles made of reinforced plastics are also available, but their high cost restricts application.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Each structure must be designed for the loads imposed on it by the conductors.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] The weight of the conductor must be supported, as well as dynamic loads due to wind and ice accumulation, and effects of vibration.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Where conductors are in a straight line, towers need only resist the weight since the tension in the conductors approximately balances with no resultant force on the structure.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Flexible conductors supported at their ends approximate the form of a catenary, and much of the analysis for construction of transmission lines relies on the properties of this form.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Depending on the design criteria for a particular line, semi-flexible type structures may rely on the weight of the conductors to be balanced on both sides of each tower.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] More rigid structures may be intended to remain standing even if one or more conductors is broken.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Such structures may be installed at intervals in power lines to limit the scale of cascading tower failures.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Foundations for tower structures may be large and costly, particularly if the ground conditions are poor, such as in wetlands.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Each structure may be stabilized considerably by the use of guy wires to counteract some of the forces applied by the conductors.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Power lines and supporting structures can be a form of visual pollution.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] In some cases the lines are buried to avoid this, but this "undergrounding" is more expensive and therefore not common.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] For a single wood utility pole structure, a pole is placed in the ground, then three crossarms extend from this, either staggered or all to one side.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] The insulators are attached to the crossarms.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] For an "H"-type wood pole structure, two poles are placed in the ground, then a crossbar is placed on top of these, extending to both sides.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] The insulators are attached at the ends and in the middle.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Lattice tower structures have two common forms.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] One has a pyramidal base, then a vertical section, where three crossarms extend out, typically staggered.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] The strain insulators are attached to the crossarms.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Another has a pyramidal base, which extends to four support points.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] On top of this a horizontal truss-like structure is placed.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] A grounded wire is sometimes strung along the tops of the towers to provide lightning protection.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] An optical ground wire is a more advanced version with embedded optical fibers for communication.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Overhead wire markers can be mounted on the ground wire to meet International Civil Aviation Organization recommendations.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Some markers include flashing lamps for night-time warning.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] A *single-circuit transmission line* carries conductors for only one circuit.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] For a three-phase system, this implies that each tower supports three conductors.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] A *double-circuit transmission line* has two circuits.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] For three-phase systems, each tower supports and insulates six conductors.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Single phase AC-power lines as used for traction current have four conductors for two circuits.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Usually both circuits operate at the same voltage.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] In HVDC systems typically two conductors are carried per line, but in rare cases only one pole of the system is carried on a set of towers.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] In some countries like Germany most power lines with voltages above 100 kV are implemented as double, quadruple or in rare cases even hextuple power line as rights of way are rare.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Sometimes all conductors are installed with the erection of the pylons; often some circuits are installed later.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] A disadvantage of double circuit transmission lines is that maintenance can be difficult, as either work in close proximity of high voltage or switch-off of two circuits is required.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] In case of failure, both systems can be affected.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] The largest double-circuit transmission line is the Kita-Iwaki Powerline.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Insulators must support the conductors and withstand both the normal operating voltage and surges due to switching and lightning.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Insulators are broadly classified as either pin-type, which support the conductor above the structure, or suspension type, where the conductor hangs below the structure.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] The invention of the strain insulator was a critical factor in allowing higher voltages to be used.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] At the end of the 19th century, the limited electrical strength of telegraph-style pin insulators limited the voltage to no more than 69,000 volts.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Up to about 33 kV (69 kV in North America) both types are commonly used.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] At higher voltages only suspension-type insulators are common for overhead conductors.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Insulators are usually made of wet-process porcelain or toughened glass, with increasing use of glass-reinforced polymer insulators.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] However, with rising voltage levels, polymer insulators (silicone rubber based) are a lower cost, shorter life span option.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] China has already developed polymer insulators having a highest system voltage of 1100 kV and India is currently developing a 1200 kV (highest system voltage) line which will initially be charged with 400 kV to be upgraded to a 1200 kV line.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Suspension insulators are made of multiple units, with the number of unit insulator disks increasing at higher voltages.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] The number of disks is chosen based on line voltage, lightning withstand requirement, altitude, and environmental factors such as fog, pollution, or salt spray.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] In cases where these conditions are suboptimal, longer insulators must be used.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Longer insulators with longer creepage distance for leakage current, are required in these cases.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Strain insulators must be strong enough mechanically to support the full weight of the span of conductor, as well as loads due to ice accumulation, and wind.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Porcelain insulators may have a semi-conductive glaze finish, so that a small current (a few milliamperes) passes through the insulator.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] This warms the surface slightly and reduces the effect of fog and dirt accumulation.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] The semiconducting glaze also ensures a more even distribution of voltage along the length of the chain of insulator units.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Polymer insulators by nature have hydrophobic characteristics providing for improved wet performance.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Also, studies have shown that the specific creepage distance required in polymer insulators is much lower than that required in porcelain or glass.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Additionally, the mass of polymer insulators (especially in higher voltages) is approximately 50% to 30% less than that of a comparative porcelain or glass string.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Better pollution and wet performance is leading to the increased use of such insulators.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Insulators for very high voltages, exceeding 200 kV, may have grading rings installed at their terminals.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] This improves the electric field distribution around the insulator and makes it more resistant to flash-over during voltage surges.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] The most common conductor in use for transmission today is aluminum conductor steel reinforced (ACSR).
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Also seeing much use is all-aluminum-alloy conductor (AAAC).
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Aluminum is used because it has about half the weight of a comparable resistance copper cable (though larger diameter due to lower specific conductivity), as well as being cheaper.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Copper was more popular in the past and is still in use, especially at lower voltages and for grounding.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] While larger conductors lose less energy due to lower electrical resistance, they are more costly than smaller conductors.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] An optimization rule called *Kelvin's Law* (named for Lord Kelvin) states that the optimum size of conductor for a line is found when the cost of the energy wasted in the conductor is equal to the annual interest paid on that portion of the line construction cost due to the size of the conductors.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] The optimization problem is made more complex by additional factors such as varying annual load, varying cost of installation, and the discrete sizes of cable that are commonly made.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Since a conductor is a flexible object with uniform weight per unit length, the shape of a conductor strung between two towers approximates that of a catenary.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] The sag of the conductor (vertical distance between the highest and lowest point of the curve) varies depending on the temperature and additional load such as ice cover.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] A minimum overhead clearance must be maintained for safety.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Such conductors which offer reduced thermal sag are known as composite core conductors or type 4 HTLS conductors, and include brand names from various manufacturers such as ACCC, ACCR, HVCRC and Losag.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] In lieu of steel core strands that are often used to increase overall conductor strength, HTLS conductors use a composite core made principally of carbon fiber that offers a coefficient of thermal expansion about 1/10 of that of steel.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] While the composite core is nonconductive, it is substantially lighter and stronger than steel, which allows the incorporation of 28% more aluminum (using compact trapezoidal-shaped strands) without any diameter or weight penalty.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] The added aluminum content helps reduce line losses by 25 to 40% compared to other conductors of the same diameter and weight, depending upon electric current.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] The carbon core conductor's reduced thermal sag allows it to carry up to twice the current ("ampacity") compared to all-aluminum conductor (AAC) or ACSR.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] The power lines and their surroundings must be maintained by linemen, sometimes assisted by helicopters with pressure washers or circular saws which may work three times faster.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] However this work often occurs in the dangerous areas of the Helicopter height–velocity diagram, and the pilot must be qualified for this "human external cargo" method.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] For transmission of power across long distances, high voltage transmission is employed.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Transmission higher than 132 kV poses the problem of corona discharge, which causes significant power loss and interference with communication circuits.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] To reduce this corona effect, it is preferable to use more than one conductor per phase, or bundled conductors.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Bundle conductors consist of several parallel cables connected at intervals by spacers, often in a cylindrical configuration.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] The optimum number of conductors depends on the current rating, but typically higher-voltage lines also have higher current.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] American Electric Power is building 765 kV lines using six conductors per phase in a bundle.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Spacers must resist the forces due to wind, and magnetic forces during a short-circuit.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Bundled conductors reduce the voltage gradient in the vicinity of the line.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] This reduces the possibility of corona discharge.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] At extra high voltage, the electric field gradient at the surface of a single conductor is high enough to ionize air, which wastes power, generates unwanted audible noise and interferes with communication systems.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] The field surrounding a bundle of conductors is similar to the field that would surround a single, very large conductor—this produces lower gradients which mitigates issues associated with high field strength.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] The transmission efficiency is improved as loss due to corona effect is countered.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Bundled conductors cool themselves more efficiently due to the increased surface area of the conductors, further reducing line losses.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] When transmitting alternating current, bundle conductors also avoid the reduction in ampacity of a single large conductor due to the skin effect.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] A bundle conductor also has lower reactance, compared to a single conductor.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] While wind resistance is higher, wind-induced oscillation can be damped at bundle spacers.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] The ice and wind loading of bundled conductors will be greater than a single conductor of the same total cross section, and bundled conductors are more difficult to install than single conductors.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Overhead power lines are often equipped with a ground conductor (shield wire, static wire, or overhead earth wire).
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] The ground conductor is usually grounded (earthed) at the top of the supporting structure, to minimize the likelihood of direct lightning strikes to the phase conductors.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] In circuits with earthed neutral, it also serves as a parallel path with the earth for fault currents.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Very high-voltage transmission lines may have two ground conductors.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] These are either at the outermost ends of the highest cross beam, at two V-shaped mast points, or at a separate cross arm.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Older lines may use surge arresters every few spans in place of a shield wire; this configuration is typically found in the more rural areas of the United States.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] By protecting the line from lightning, the design of apparatus in substations is simplified due to lower stress on insulation.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Shield wires on transmission lines may include optical fibers (optical ground wires/OPGW), used for communication and control of the power system.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] At some HVDC converter stations, the ground wire is used also as the electrode line to connect to a distant grounding electrode.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] This allows the HVDC system to use the earth as one conductor.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] The ground conductor is mounted on small insulators bridged by lightning arrestors above the phase conductors.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] The insulation prevents electrochemical corrosion of the pylon.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] On some power lines for very high voltages in the former Soviet Union, the ground wire is used for PLC systems and mounted on insulators at the pylons.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Overhead insulated cables are rarely used, usually for short distances (less than a kilometer).
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Insulated cables can be directly fastened to structures without insulating supports.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] An overhead line with bare conductors insulated by air is typically less costly than a cable with insulated conductors.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] A more common approach is "covered" line wire.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] It is treated as bare cable, but often is safer for wildlife, as the insulation on the cables increases the likelihood of a large-wing-span raptor to survive a brush with the lines, and reduces the overall danger of the lines slightly.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] These types of lines are often seen in the eastern United States and in heavily wooded areas, where tree-line contact is likely.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] The only pitfall is cost, as insulated wire is often costlier than its bare counterpart.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Many utility companies implement covered line wire as jumper material where the wires are often closer to each other on the pole, such as an underground riser/pothead, and on reclosers, cutouts and the like.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Because power lines can suffer from aeroelastic flutter driven by wind, Stockbridge dampers are often attached to the lines to reduce the vibrations.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] A compact overhead transmission line requires a smaller right of way than a standard overhead powerline.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Conductors must not get too close to each other.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] This can be achieved either by short span lengths and insulating crossbars, or by separating the conductors in the span with insulators.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] The first type is easier to build as it does not require insulators in the span, which may be difficult to install and to maintain.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Compact transmission lines may be designed for voltage upgrade of existing lines to increase the power that can be transmitted on an existing right of way.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Low voltage overhead lines may use either bare conductors carried on glass or ceramic insulators or an aerial bundled cable system.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Overhead lines or overhead wires are used to transmit electrical energy to trams, trolleybuses or trains.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Overhead line is designed on the principle of one or more overhead wires situated over rail tracks.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Feeder stations at regular intervals along the overhead line supply power from the high-voltage grid.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] For some cases low-frequency AC is used, and distributed by a special traction current network.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Overhead lines are also occasionally used to supply transmitting antennas, especially for efficient transmission of long, medium and short waves.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] For this purpose a staggered array line is often used.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Along a staggered array line the conductor cables for the supply of the earth net of the transmitting antenna are attached on the exterior of a ring, while the conductor inside the ring, is fastened to insulators leading to the high-voltage standing feeder of the antenna.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Use of the area below an overhead line is limited because objects must not come too close to the energized conductors.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Overhead lines and structures may shed ice, creating a hazard.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Radio reception can be impaired under a power line, due both to shielding of a receiver antenna by the overhead conductors, and by partial discharge at insulators and sharp points of the conductors which creates radio noise.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] In the area surrounding the overhead lines it is dangerous to risk interference; e.g. flying kites or balloons, using ladders or operating machinery.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Overhead distribution and transmission lines near airfields are often marked on maps, and the lines themselves marked with conspicuous plastic reflectors, to warn pilots of the presence of conductors.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Construction of overhead power lines, especially in wilderness areas, may have significant environmental effects.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Environmental studies for such projects may consider the effect of bush clearing, changed migration routes for migratory animals, possible access by predators and humans along transmission corridors, disturbances of fish habitat at stream crossings, and other effects.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] General aviation, hang gliding, paragliding, skydiving, balloon, and kite flying must avoid accidental contact with power lines.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Nearly every kite product warns users to stay away from power lines.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Deaths occur when aircraft crash into power lines.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Some power lines are marked with obstruction markers, especially near air strips or over waterways that may support floatplane operations.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] The placement of power lines sometimes use up sites that would otherwise be used by hang gliders.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] The first transmission of electrical impulses over an extended distance was demonstrated on July 14, 1729 by the physicist Stephen Gray.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] The demonstration used damp hemp cords suspended by silk threads (the low resistance of metallic conductors not being appreciated at the time).
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] However the first practical use of overhead lines was in the context of telegraphy.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] By 1837 experimental commercial telegraph systems ran as far as 20 km (13 miles).
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Electric power transmission was accomplished in 1882 with the first high-voltage transmission between Munich and Miesbach (60 km).
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] 1891 saw the construction of the first three-phase alternating current overhead line on the occasion of the International Electricity Exhibition in Frankfurt, between Lauffen and Frankfurt.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] In 1912 the first 110 kV-overhead power line entered service followed by the first 220 kV-overhead power line in 1923.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] In the 1920s RWE AG built the first overhead line for this voltage and in 1926 built a Rhine crossing with the pylons of Voerde, two masts 138 meters high.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] In 1953, the first 345 kV line was put into service by American Electric Power in the United States.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] In Germany in 1957 the first 380 kV overhead power line was commissioned (between the transformer station and Rommerskirchen).
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] In the same year the overhead line traversing of the Strait of Messina went into service in Italy, whose pylons served the Elbe crossing 1.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] This was used as the model for the building of the Elbe crossing 2 in the second half of the 1970s which saw the construction of the highest overhead line pylons of the world.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Earlier, in 1952, the first 380 kV line was put into service in Sweden, in 1000 km (625 miles) between the more populated areas in the south and the largest hydroelectric power stations in the north.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] Starting from 1967 in Russia, and also in the USA and Canada, overhead lines for voltage of 765 kV were built.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] In 1985 overhead power line was built in Soviet Union between Kokshetau and the power station at Ekibastuz, this was a three-phase alternating current line at 1150 kV.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] In 1999, in Japan the first powerline designed for 1000 kV with 2 circuits were built, the Kita-Iwaki Powerline.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] In 2002 the building of the highest overhead line commenced in China, the Yangtze River Crossing, its two 346.5 m (1,137 ft) high suspension towers beginning service in 2004.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] In the 21st century, replacing steel with carbon fiber cores (advanced reconductoring) became a way for utilities to increase transmission capacity without increasing the amount of land used.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] An overhead power line is one example of a transmission line.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] At power system frequencies, many useful simplifications can be made for lines of typical lengths.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] For analysis of power systems, the distributed resistance, series inductance, shunt leakage resistance and shunt capacitance can be replaced with suitable lumped values or simplified networks.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] A short length of a power line (less than 80 km) can be approximated with a resistance in series with an inductance and ignoring the shunt admittances.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] This value is not the total impedance of the line, but rather the series impedance per unit length of line.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] For a longer length of line (80–250 km), a shunt capacitance is added to the model.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] In this case it is common to distribute half of the total capacitance to each side of the line.
[src:transmission-distribution/overhead-power-line] As a result, the power line can be represented as a two-port network, such as with ABCD parameters.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] In electrical engineering, a **transformer** is a passive component that transfers electrical energy from one electrical circuit to another circuit, or multiple circuits.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] A varying current in any coil of the transformer produces a varying magnetic flux in the transformer's core, which induces a varying electromotive force (EMF) across any other coils wound around the same core.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Electrical energy can be transferred between separate coils without a metallic (conductive) connection between the two circuits.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Faraday's law of induction, discovered in 1831, describes the induced voltage effect in any coil due to a changing magnetic flux encircled by the coil.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Transformers are used to change AC voltage levels, such transformers being termed *step-up* or *step-down* type to increase or decrease voltage level, respectively.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Transformers can also be used to provide galvanic isolation between circuits as well as to couple stages of signal-processing circuits.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Since the invention of the first constant-potential transformer in 1885, transformers have become essential for the transmission, distribution, and utilization of alternating current electric power.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] A wide range of transformer designs is encountered in electronic and electric power applications.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Transformers range in size from RF transformers less than a cubic centimeter in volume, to units weighing hundreds of tons used to interconnect the power grid.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] An ideal transformer is linear, lossless, and perfectly coupled.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Perfect coupling implies infinitely high core magnetic permeability and winding inductance and zero net magnetomotive force (i.e.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] A varying current in the transformer's primary winding creates a varying magnetic flux in the transformer core, which is also encircled by the secondary winding.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] This varying flux at the secondary winding induces a varying electromotive force or voltage in the secondary winding.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] This electromagnetic induction phenomenon is the basis of transformer action and, in accordance with Lenz's law, the secondary current so produced creates a flux equal and opposite to that produced by the primary winding.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] The windings are wound around a core of infinitely high magnetic permeability so that all of the magnetic flux passes through both the primary and secondary windings.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] With a voltage source connected to the primary winding and a load connected to the secondary winding, the transformer currents flow in the indicated directions and the core magnetomotive force cancels to zero.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] According to Faraday's law, since the same magnetic flux passes through both the primary and secondary windings in an ideal transformer, a voltage is induced in each winding proportional to its number of turns.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] The transformer winding voltage ratio is equal to the winding turns ratio.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] An ideal transformer is a reasonable approximation for a typical commercial transformer, with voltage ratio and winding turns ratio both being inversely proportional to the corresponding current ratio.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] The load impedance *referred* to the primary circuit is equal to the turns ratio squared times the secondary circuit load impedance.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] The ideal transformer model neglects many basic linear aspects of real transformers, including unavoidable losses and inefficiencies.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] (c) similar to an inductor, parasitic capacitance and self-resonance phenomenon due to the electric field distribution.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Inclusion of capacitance into the transformer model is complicated, and is rarely attempted; the 'real' transformer model's equivalent circuit shown below does not include parasitic capacitance.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] However, the capacitance effect can be measured by comparing open-circuit inductance, i.e., the inductance of a primary winding when the secondary circuit is open, to a short-circuit inductance when the secondary winding is shorted.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] The ideal transformer model assumes that all flux generated by the primary winding links all the turns of every winding, including itself.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] In practice, some flux traverses paths that take it outside the windings.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Such flux is termed *leakage flux*, and results in leakage inductance in series with the mutually coupled transformer windings.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Leakage flux results in energy being alternately stored in and discharged from the magnetic fields with each cycle of the power supply.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] It is not directly a power loss, but results in inferior voltage regulation, causing the secondary voltage not to be directly proportional to the primary voltage, particularly under heavy load.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Transformers are therefore normally designed to have very low leakage inductance.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] In some applications, increased leakage is desired, and long magnetic paths, air gaps, or magnetic bypass shunts may deliberately be introduced in a transformer design to limit the short-circuit current it will supply.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Leaky transformers may be used to supply loads that exhibit negative resistance, such as electric arcs, mercury- and sodium- vapor lamps and neon signs or for safely handling loads that become periodically short-circuited such as electric arc welders.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Air gaps are also used to keep a transformer from saturating, especially audio-frequency transformers in circuits that have a DC component flowing in the windings.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] A saturable reactor exploits saturation of the core to control alternating current.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Knowledge of leakage inductance is also useful when transformers are operated in parallel.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] It can be shown that if the percent impedance and associated winding leakage reactance-to-resistance (*X*/*R*) ratio of two transformers were the same, the transformers would share the load power in proportion to their respective ratings.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] However, the impedance tolerances of commercial transformers are significant.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Also, the impedance and X/R ratio of different capacity transformers tend to vary.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Referring to the diagram, a practical transformer's physical behavior may be represented by an equivalent circuit model, which can incorporate an ideal transformer.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] In normal course of circuit equivalence transformation, *R*S and *X*S are in practice usually referred to the primary side by multiplying these impedances by the turns ratio squared, (*N*P/*N*S) 2 = a2.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Core losses are caused mostly by hysteresis and eddy current effects in the core and are proportional to the square of the core flux for operation at a given frequency.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] The finite permeability core requires a magnetizing current *I*M to maintain mutual flux in the core.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Magnetizing current is in phase with the flux, the relationship between the two being non-linear due to saturation effects.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] However, all impedances of the equivalent circuit shown are by definition linear and such non-linearity effects are not typically reflected in transformer equivalent circuits.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] With sinusoidal supply, core flux lags the induced EMF by 90°.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] With open-circuited secondary winding, magnetizing branch current *I*0 equals transformer no-load current.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] The resulting model, though sometimes termed 'exact' equivalent circuit based on linearity assumptions, retains a number of approximations.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Analysis may be simplified by assuming that magnetizing branch impedance is relatively high and relocating the branch to the left of the primary impedances.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] This introduces error but allows combination of primary and referred secondary resistances and reactance by simple summation as two series impedances.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Transformer equivalent circuit impedance and transformer ratio parameters can be derived from the following tests: open-circuit test, short-circuit test, winding resistance test, and transformer ratio test.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] A dot convention is often used in transformer circuit diagrams, nameplates or terminal markings to define the relative polarity of transformer windings.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Positively increasing instantaneous current entering the primary winding's 'dot' end induces positive polarity voltage exiting the secondary winding's 'dot' end.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Three-phase transformers used in electric power systems will have a nameplate that indicates the phase relationships between their terminals.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] This may be in the form of a phasor diagram, or using an alpha-numeric code to show the type of internal connection (wye or delta) for each winding.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] The EMF of a transformer at a given flux increases with frequency.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] By operating at higher frequencies, transformers can be physically more compact because a given core is able to transfer more power without reaching saturation, and fewer turns are needed to achieve the same impedance.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] However, properties such as core loss and conductor skin effect also increase with frequency.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Aircraft and military equipment employ 400 Hz power supplies, which reduce core and winding weight.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Conversely, frequencies used for some railway electrification systems were much lower (e.g.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] 16.7 Hz and 25 Hz) than normal utility frequencies (50–60 Hz) for historical reasons concerned mainly with the limitations of early electric traction motors.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Consequently, the transformers used to step down the high overhead line voltages were much larger and heavier for the same power rating than those required for the higher frequencies.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Operation of a transformer at its designed voltage but at a higher frequency than intended will lead to reduced magnetizing current.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] At a lower frequency, the magnetizing current will increase.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Operation of a large transformer at other than its design frequency may require assessment of voltages, losses, and cooling to establish if safe operation is practical.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Transformers may require protective relays to protect the transformer from overvoltage at higher than rated frequency.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] One example is in traction transformers used for electric multiple unit and high-speed train service operating across regions with different electrical standards.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] The converter equipment and traction transformers have to accommodate different input frequencies and voltage (ranging from as high as 50 Hz down to 16.7 Hz and rated up to 25 kV).
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] At much higher frequencies, the transformer core size required drops dramatically: a physically small transformer can handle power levels that would require a massive iron core at mains frequency.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] The development of switching power semiconductor devices made switched-mode power supplies (SMPSs) viable, to generate a high frequency, then change the voltage level with a small transformer.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Transformers for higher frequency applications, such as SMPSs, typically use core materials with much lower hysteresis and eddy-current losses than those for 50/60 Hz.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Primary examples are iron-powder and ferrite cores.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] The lower frequency-dependent losses of these cores often is at the expense of flux density at saturation.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] For instance, ferrite saturation occurs at a substantially lower flux density than laminated iron.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Large power transformers are vulnerable to insulation failure due to transient voltages with high-frequency components, such as those caused by switching or by lightning.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Transformer energy losses are dominated by winding and core losses.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Transformers' efficiency tends to improve with increasing transformer capacity.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] As transformer losses vary with load, it is often useful to tabulate no-load loss, full-load loss, half-load loss, and so on.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Hysteresis and eddy current losses are constant at all load levels and dominate at no load, while winding loss increases as load increases.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] The no-load loss can be significant, so that even an idle transformer constitutes a drain on the electrical supply.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Designing energy efficient transformers for lower loss requires a larger core, good-quality silicon steel, or even amorphous steel for the core and thicker wire, increasing initial cost.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] The choice of construction represents a trade-off between initial cost and operating cost.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] cause the winding's resistance and, hence, losses to increase.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] is the maximum flux density, the empirical exponent of which varies from about 1.4 to 1.8 but is often given as 1.6 for iron.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] are induced in the conductive metal transformer core by the changing magnetic field, and this current, flowing through the resistance of the iron, dissipates energy as heat in the core.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] The eddy current loss is a complex function of the square of supply frequency and inverse square of the material thickness.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Eddy current losses can be reduced by making the core of a stack of laminations (thin plates) electrically insulated from each other, rather than a solid block; all transformers operating at low frequencies use laminated or similar cores.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Leakage inductance is by itself largely lossless, since energy supplied to its magnetic fields is returned to the supply with the next half-cycle.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] However, any leakage flux that intercepts nearby conductive materials, such as the transformer's support structure, will give rise to eddy currents and be converted to heat.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] There are also radiative losses due to the oscillating magnetic field, but these are usually small.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] In addition to magnetostriction, the alternating magnetic field causes fluctuating forces between the primary and secondary windings.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] This energy incites vibration transmission in interconnected metalwork, thus amplifying audible transformer hum.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Closed-core transformers are constructed in 'core form' or 'shell form'.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] When windings surround the core, the transformer is core form; when windings are surrounded by the core, the transformer is shell form.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Shell form design may be more prevalent than core form design for distribution transformer applications due to the relative ease in stacking the core around winding coils.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Core form design tends to, as a general rule, be more economical, and therefore more prevalent, than shell form design for high voltage power transformer applications at the lower end of their voltage and power rating ranges (less than or equal to, nominally, 230 kV or 75 MVA).
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] At higher voltage and power ratings, shell form transformers tend to be more prevalent.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Transformers for use at power or audio frequencies typically have cores made of high permeability silicon steel.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] The steel has a permeability many times that of free space and the core thus serves to greatly reduce the magnetizing current and confine the flux to a path which closely couples the windings.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Early transformer developers soon realized that cores constructed from solid iron resulted in prohibitive eddy current losses, and their designs mitigated this effect with cores consisting of bundles of insulated iron wires.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Later designs constructed the core by stacking layers of thin steel laminations, a principle that has remained in use.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Each lamination is insulated from its neighbors by a thin non-conducting layer of insulation.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] The transformer universal EMF equation can be used to calculate the core cross-sectional area for a preferred level of magnetic flux.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] The effect of laminations is to confine eddy currents to highly elliptical paths that enclose little flux, and so reduce their magnitude.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Thinner laminations reduce losses, but are more laborious and expensive to construct.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Thin laminations are generally used on high-frequency transformers, with some very thin steel laminations able to operate up to 10 kHz.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] One common design of laminated core is made from interleaved stacks of E-shaped steel sheets capped with I-shaped pieces, leading to its name of **E-I transformer**.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Such a design tends to exhibit more losses, but is very economical to manufacture.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] The cut-core or C-core type is made by winding a steel strip around a rectangular form and then bonding the layers together.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] It is then cut in two, forming two C shapes, and the core is assembled by binding the two C halves together with a steel strap.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] They have the advantage that the flux is always oriented parallel to the metal grains, reducing reluctance.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] A steel core's remanence means that it retains a static magnetic field when power is removed.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] When power is then reapplied, the residual field will cause a high inrush current until the effect of the remaining magnetism is reduced, usually after a few cycles of the applied AC waveform.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Overcurrent protection devices such as fuses must be selected to allow this harmless inrush to pass.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] On transformers connected to long, overhead power transmission lines, induced currents due to geomagnetic disturbances during solar storms can cause saturation of the core and operation of transformer protection devices.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Distribution transformers can achieve low no-load losses by using cores made with low-loss high-permeability silicon steel or amorphous (non-crystalline) metal alloy.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] The higher initial cost of the core material is offset over the life of the transformer by its lower losses at light load.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Powdered iron cores are used in circuits such as switch-mode power supplies that operate above mains frequencies and up to a few tens of kilohertz.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] These materials combine high magnetic permeability with high bulk electrical resistivity.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] For frequencies extending beyond the VHF band, cores made from non-conductive magnetic ceramic materials called ferrites are common.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Some radio-frequency transformers also have movable cores (sometimes called 'slugs') which allow adjustment of the coupling coefficient (and bandwidth) of tuned radio-frequency circuits.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Toroidal transformers are built around a ring-shaped core, which, depending on operating frequency, is made from a long strip of silicon steel or permalloy wound into a coil, powdered iron, or ferrite.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] A strip construction ensures that the grain boundaries are optimally aligned, improving the transformer's efficiency by reducing the core's reluctance.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] The closed ring shape eliminates air gaps inherent in the construction of an E-I core.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] The cross-section of the ring is usually square or rectangular, but more expensive cores with circular cross-sections are also available.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] The primary and secondary coils are often wound concentrically to cover the entire surface of the core.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] This minimizes the length of wire needed and provides screening to minimize the core's magnetic field from generating electromagnetic interference.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Toroidal transformers are more efficient than the cheaper laminated E-I types for a similar power level.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] The main disadvantages are higher cost and limited power capacity (see Classification parameters below).
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Because of the lack of a residual gap in the magnetic path, toroidal transformers also tend to exhibit higher inrush current, compared to laminated E-I types.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Ferrite toroidal cores are used at higher frequencies, typically between a few tens of kilohertz and hundreds of megahertz, to reduce losses, physical size, and weight of inductive components.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] A drawback of toroidal transformer construction is the higher labor cost of winding.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] This is because it is necessary to pass the entire length of a coil winding through the core aperture each time a single turn is added to the coil.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] As a consequence, toroidal transformers rated more than a few kVA are uncommon.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Relatively few toroids are offered with power ratings above 10 kVA, and practically none above 25 kVA.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] Small distribution transformers may achieve some of the benefits of a toroidal core by splitting it and forcing it open, then inserting a bobbin containing primary and secondary windings.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] A transformer can be produced by placing the windings near each other, an arrangement termed an "air-core" transformer.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] An air-core transformer eliminates loss due to hysteresis in the core material.
[src:transmission-distribution/power-transformer] The magnetizing inductance is drastically reduced by the lack of a magnetic core, resulting in large magnetizing currents and losses if used at low frequencies.
